aVIdeas aren\u2019t formed in a vacuum. That\u2019s why we asked the members of this year\u2019s POLITICO 50 list to name the best book they read this year. Their responses\u2014from Steve Bannon\u2019s recommended reading on the French Revolution, to the thesis on media mindlessness suggested by Jon Favreau\u2014offer insights into the intellectual conversations shaping American politics today.\u000a\u000aIn fact, the 25 book recommendations we received this year exhibit a few trends. Some attempt to, or inadvertently could, explain the moment we live in. Others are concerted efforts to escape the moment we live in. And a few were written by former and current members of the POLITICO 50.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000aCitizens: A Chronicle of the French Revolution, by Simon Schama \u2014Steve Bannon\u000a\u000aTwitter and Tear Gas, by Zeynep Tufekci \u2014Leah Greenberg and Ezra Levin\u000a\u000aWinston Churchill: A Life, by John Keegan. \u201cHe makes it hard to sit still and keep quiet when there\u2019s a fight that you should be fighting.\u201d \u2014Andy Slavitt\u000a\u000aThe End of the Asian Century, by Michael R. Auslin \u2014Mick Mulvaney\u000a\u000aHillbilly Elegy, by J.D. Vance \u2014Lonnie Bunch III\u000a\u000aHitler: Ascent, 1889-1939, by Volker Ullrich \u2014Norm Eisen\u000a\u000aThe Political Theory of the American Founding, by Thomas G. West \u2014Charles Kesler\u000a\u000aThe Ideas Industry, by Daniel W. Drezner \u2014Tom Nichols\u000a\u000aThe Handmaid\u2019s Tale, by Margaret Atwood \u2014Amy Siskind\u000a\u000aStrangers in Their Own Land, by Arlie Russell Hochschild \u2014Mitch Landrieu\u000a\u000aAmusing Ourselves to Death, by Neil Postman \u2014Jon Favreau\u000a\u000aThe War on Cops, by Heather Mac Donald \u2014Steven H. Cook\u000a\u000aEveryone Matters, by Pat Thomas \u2014Aramis Ayala\u000a\u000aA City Dreaming, by Daniel Polansky \u2014Richard Reeves\u000a\u000aThe Mountains of Parnassus, by Czeslaw Milosz, and Johnny\u2019s Cash, Charley\u2019s Pride: Lasting Legends and Untold Adventures in Country Music, by Peter Cooper \u2014Russell Moore\u000a\u000aOption B, by Sheryl Sandberg and Adam Grant. I\u2019m also enjoying Hillbilly Elegy, by J.D. Vance. \u2014Aparna Mathur\u000a\u000aRoxana, by Daniel Defoe \u2014Sonja Trauss\u000a\u000aHomegoing, by Yaa Gyasi \u2014Lynn Nottage\u000a\u000aEverything I Don\u2019t Remember, by Jonas Hassen Khemiri \u2014Masha Gessen\u000a\u000aThe Undoing of Death, by Fleming Rutledge \u2014John Kasich\u000a\u000aDream Hoarders, by Richard Reeves. Although I don\u2019t agree with everything he says, it\u2019s a compelling read. \u2014William Darity Jr.\u000a\u000aThe Ideas Issue The POLITICO 50 The ideas blowing up American politics\u2014and the people behind them. Our annual list.\u000a\u000aPrince of Darkness, by Shane White (about Wall Street\u2019s first African-American millionaire, in the 1830s). \u2014Neal Katyal\u000a\u000aThe Daily Stoic: 366 Meditations on Wisdom, Perseverance, and the Art of Living, by Ryan Holiday and Stephen Hanselman \u2014Brad Thor\u000a\u000aHunger, by Roxane Gay \u2014Cathy O\u2019Neil\u000a\u000aThis story tagged under: Books\u000a\u000aReading\u000a\u000aPolitico 50
