aVThe appointment of a prominent journalist to Macron's team fits into a major rejigging of his media strategy | Ludovic Marin/AFP via Getty Images Macron signs up journalist as spokesman amid PR shakeup The outspoken Bruno Roger-Petit joins will be responsible for \u2018broadcasting the Elysée\u2019s public message.\u2019\u000a\u000aPARIS \u2014 Emmanuel Macron\u2019s office named TV journalist and opinion writer Bruno Roger-Petit as a spokesman Tuesday, completing a shakeup of the French president\u2019s communications team amid falling poll scores.\u000a\u000aRoger-Petit\u2019s hiring came after the Elysée presidential palace this summer brought in three new press attachés, two of them from Macron\u2019s centrist La République en Marche movement.\u000a\u000aRoger-Petit, named as a \u201cspokesman and adviser to the president,\u201d will be tasked with \u201cbroadcasting the Elysée\u2019s public message\u201d via \u201cany means at his disposal, notably the presidency\u2019s Twitter account,\u201d a statement from Macron\u2019s office said.\u000a\u000aThe appointment of a prominent journalist to Macron\u2019s team fits into a major rejigging of his media strategy.\u000a\u000aNo longer concerned with preserving his mystique, Macron will speak out more frequently to explain his reform agenda and fight back against plummeting approval scores.\u000a\u000aThe president is also pressing his cabinet members and staff to speak out in his defense on TV and radio.\u000a\u000aBy hiring Roger-Petit, a no-holds-barred debater, the Elysée gains a combative presence already known to much of the public after stints as a news presenter and a frequent guest on popular talk shows.\u000a\u000aMost recently, he wrote political commentary for Challenges, a business magazine.\u000a\u000aA prolific tweeter with more than 70,000 followers, Roger-Petit deleted his account minutes after his appointment was made public.\u000a\u000aBut he will have trouble hiding years of strong opinions, including an article he penned in July headlined \u201cWhy Macron must absolutely abandon Jupiter\u201d that seemed to presage the president\u2019s about-face on communications. The \u201cJupiterian\u201d concept was developed by Macron\u2019s team in the last few months of the presidential campaign to illustrate his vision of the presidency. Jupiter is the supreme god of Roman mythology \u2014 god of the sky, thunder and lightning.\u000a\u000aRoger-Petit may have been pulling his punches in that article. In early 2016 he wrote that Macron had \u201cstolen everything\u201d from former Prime Minister Manuel Valls.\u000a\u000aRoger-Petit\u2019s big challenge now is to turn the tide of negative opinion while also avoiding the fate of another journalist-turned-spokeswoman, Laurence Haim. Formerly the Washington correspondent for iTele, Haim was hired as a spokeswoman during Macron\u2019s campaign but did not win a government appointment, and went back to journalism.
