aVBOLOGNA, Italy \u2014 Once, the Northern League campaigned for the break-up of Italy. Now, the party\u2019s challenge is how to reconcile its separatist roots with the national ambitions of its leader, Matteo Salvini.\u000a\u000aThe ultimate aim of the Northern League, according to its constitution, is the independence of \u201cPadania\u201d \u2014 the party\u2019s name for the broad region across northern Italy it argues should constitute an independent state. But you wouldn\u2019t know it since Salvini became leader in 2013.\u000a\u000aThe Northern League\u2019s bellicose leader has propelled his once marginal party into one of the largest in Italy by hammering on topics like crime, terrorism, immigration, and the ills of the European Union. Regional autonomy \u2014 once his party\u2019s defining issue \u2014 has almost completely dropped out of his register.\u000a\u000aIf Salvini is to maintain that so-far successful strategy ahead of parliamentary elections expected early next year, he will have to overcome resistance by some of that party\u2019s old guard \u2014 including its two most prominent regional leaders, Luca Zaia, president of Italy\u2019s Veneto region, and Roberto Maroni, Salvini\u2019s predecessor who is now president of Lombardy, the region around Milan.\u000a\u000aLombardy and Veneto, the party\u2019s two electoral strongholds, are due to hold advisory referendums on October 22 asking voters whether they support more autonomous powers for the regional governments. The measures are expected to pass overwhelmingly; the true test will be turnout.\u000a\u000aIf the two Northern League leaders can mobilize numbers and show the issue matters to people, it would build momentum for their party ahead of a general election expected early next year. It could also provide a platform for the popular Zaia to challenge Salvini over the direction he has taken the party.\u000a\u000aThis transformation of the Northern League is a curious chapter in the long struggle between regionalism and centralism in Italy.\u000a\u000aAsked why the Northern League has changed its focus, Salvini\u2019s allies say that issues like immigration are so urgent that the party\u2019s long-term goals can wait.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe League responds to the questions of the time,\u201d said Massimiliano Fedriga, the party\u2019s leader in the lower house, who is close to Salvini. \u201cWe can\u2019t give the responses to citizens today which we gave 20 or 30 years ago. This is normal. We are responding to the needs of people.\u201d\u000a\u000aCan the center hold?\u000a\u000aThis transformation of the Northern League is a curious chapter in the long struggle between regionalism and centralism in Italy, which goes back to its creation out of a patchwork of fiefdoms in the 19th century.\u000a\u000aItaly has 20 regions: fifteen have a small measure of tax and spending ability, and five have the deeper autonomous powers to which the Northern League in Lombardy and Veneto aspires.\u000a\u000aAll five special autonomous regions \u2014 the islands Sicily and Sardinia, and three areas that border Austria and France \u2014 are geographically distant from Rome and have prevalent local languages that differ from standard Italian.\u000a\u000aSalvini took over the leadership at a low point, following a disastrous national election and an embezzlement scandal that forced the resignation of senior party figures.\u000a\u000aHis reinvention of the Northern League has made it the most popular party on the right, approaching 15 percent in opinion polls, just ahead of former Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi\u2019s Forza Italia.\u000a\u000aSalvini\u2019s open ambition is to lead a coalition of the right into government next year, and polls indicate he might just be able to do it.\u000a\u000aThe bearded firebrand won an endorsement of his country-wide strategy in the party\u2019s national congress in May. He was reelected leader with 83 percent of the vote, seeing off a challenge from a former lawmaker backed by the party\u2019s old guard, Giovanni Fava, who ran on a platform of restoring the party\u2019s traditional focus on regional autonomy to \u201csave the League.\u201d Fava has become a prominent autonomy campaigner ahead of the referendums.\u000a\u000aThe party\u2019s founder and president for life Umberto Bossi begrudged Salvini\u2019s victory, complaining of low turnout and alienation of its core activist base.\u000a\u000aTransformation\u000a\u000aThe contrast between the party Bossi led and the direction in which Salvini has taken it is stark.\u000a\u000aBossi was notorious for railing against southern Italians as lazy, corrupt peasants enabled by the state to freeload off hardworking northerners.\u000a\u000aSalvini, by contrast, campaigns in Italy\u2019s furthest southern reaches, from Sicily to Calabria. He has even floated the idea of changing the party\u2019s name to discard the word \u201cNorthern.\u201d His quest to lead the right even led him to court the modern-day fascist group CasaPound, which campaigns for a muscular Italian state with radically centralist economic policies.\u000a\u000a\u201cI have an idea of the League\u2026 that fights battles not just in Lombardy and Veneto, but by the side of earthquake victims from Abruzzo, fishermen from Sicily, farmers from Apulia,\u201d he said after his reelection.\u000a\u000aClaudio Borghi Aquilini, the party\u2019s head of economic policy, described how hardened Northern League veterans met political activists from the south.\u000a\u000aThey were \u201cbasically hugging each other, realizing they were on the same side of the divide,\u201d he said. \u201cIt was a great moment.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cWe thought that our enemy was in Rome,\u201d he continued. \u201cBut we discovered all the decisions are being taken in Brussels.\u201d\u000a\u000aCrucial test\u000a\u000aSo far, Salvini has squared the autonomy referendums in Veneto and Lombardy with his national strategy by avoiding mentioning them except for to promise \u201cregionalism for all.\u201d He has indicated that should the votes pass, he will push for further referendums to devolve powers to the country\u2019s 20 regions.\u000a\u000a\u201cReferendums for autonomy? I will propose them for all of Italy,\u201d a rare tweet by him on the subject read.\u000a\u000aStill, Salvini\u2019s new style has not caught on in the Northern League\u2019s local and regional branches, where leaders still speak in terms of northern Italy versus the south.\u000a\u000aThe question is whether, with its national leadership appearing to have abandoned the issue that once defined it, the party can still count on the deeply loyal activist base it once enjoyed.\u000a\u000aOreste Rossi, a former MEP who was a founding member of the Northern League in the Piedmont region, said he left the party after Bossi\u2019s resignation when it became clear it was changing political direction.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe League once believed in Padanian independence,\u201d Rossi said. \u201cSalvini doesn\u2019t speak about regions anymore, he speaks about Italy.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIn a normal country it would be impossible to have a party like this, that has changed so radically from one week to another,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aAlong with a coterie of ex-League activists, Rossi has founded a group called \u201cGreat North,\u201d which campaigns for Italy to be divided into three states. Bossi has attended its events, and Maroni, Salvini\u2019s predecessor, openly called on the former leader not to be tempted to defect earlier this year.\u000a\u000a\u201cI am delighted if Salvini turns the League into a center-right party,\u201d Rossi said. \u201cI\u2019m sorry for my friends in the League, but it\u2019s good for us. We are the pro-independence alternative.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe party\u2019s die-hard regionalists may keep quiet as long as Salvini\u2019s strategy is bringing the party closer to national power.\u000a\u000aThe secessionist currents of the north run deep, and they aren\u2019t going anywhere fast. Veneto\u2019s governor, Zaia, has been pursuing the referendum since 2014, when he vowed he would hold a vote after a contested online poll showed strong support for Veneto\u2019s independence.\u000a\u000aHis initial ambition was to hold a vote on outright independence or for the region to keep 80 percent of tax revenues, but both options were rejected by the Constitutional Court. Ultimately, Zaia settled for merely seeking more autonomous powers through an article in the constitution that allows regions to do just that.\u000a\u000aHe picked the date of the vote as October 22: the anniversary of the 1866 plebiscite that annexed the Kingdom of Lombardy-Veneto to the Kingdom of Italy.\u000a\u000aThe party\u2019s die-hard regionalists may keep quiet as long as Salvini\u2019s strategy is bringing the party closer to national power. But an electoral slip-up would bring the conflict out into the open.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe result of the election next year will be key,\u201d said Arianna Giovannini, a lecturer at De Montfort University who has been studying Salvini\u2019s transformation of the party. \u201cIf it does well, there may be a way of containing internal tensions. There would be less of an incentive to split.\u201d
