aVHillary Clinton\u2019s new book is set to be released next week, though some excerpts have leaked out in various forms.\u000a\u000aHillary Clinton, the 2016 Democratic nominee for president, is set to release a 500-page book, explaining, as the title \u201cWhat Happened\u201d suggests, why exactly things went wrong last year. It just wasn\u2019t her time, she\u2019ll argue.\u000a\u000aTurns out it might not be a great time to release her book either.\u000a\u000aAdvertisement\u000a\u000aUnlike Republicans, who are struggling with competing factions, a stalled agenda, and a president with historically low approval ratings, Democrats in Washington are relatively unified \u2014 at least by comparison.\u000a\u000aDespite criticism for a number of missteps in 2016, the party has largely moved out of that shadow. House and Senate Democratic leaders held a joint press conference Wednesday to discuss their shared view on a number of pieces of legislation. There is new leadership at the Democratic National Committee. And we\u2019re already seeing a swarm of candidates for the midterm elections.\u000a\u000aGet Fast Forward in your inbox: Forget yesterday's news. Get what you need today in this early-morning email. Sign Up Thank you for signing up! Sign up for more newsletters here\u000a\u000aThen comes along Clinton\u2019s new book. It\u2019s set to be released next week, though some excerpts have leaked out in various forms. CNN found a copy out at a Florida bookstore Tuesday and read it overnight.\u000a\u000aAccording to the passages made public, Clinton wastes no time taking aim at her Democratic primary opponent, Senator Bernie Sanders of Vermont. She blames him for setting the framework for Trump to begin calling her Crooked Hillary. She also calls some of Sanders supporters \u201csexist\u201d and attacks their behavior online.\u000a\u000aSimon & Schuster via Associated Press Clinton\u2019s new book is called \u201cWhat Happened.\u201d\u000a\u000aIn one section that was tweeted out by a pro-Clinton Twitter account: \u201cWhen I finally challenged Bernie during a debate to name a single time I changed a position or a vote because of a financial contribution, he couldn\u2019t come up with anything,\u201d she wrote. \u201cNonetheless, his attacks caused lasting damage, making it harder to unify progressives in the general election and paving the way for Trump\u2019s \u2018Crooked Hillary\u2019 campaign.\u201d\u000a\u000aAdvertisement\u000a\u000aClinton went on: \u201cHe certainly shared my horror at the thought of Donald Trump becoming President, and I appreciate that he campaigned for me in the general election. But he isn\u2019t a Democrat \u2014 that\u2019s not a smear, that\u2019s what he says. He didn\u2019t get into the race to make sure a Democrat won the White House, he got in to disrupt the Democratic Party.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Hillary-Bernie divide has continued to simmer inside of Democratic politics through much of 2017. But the Democrats have worked to move past it, or at least to relegate it to the background. Headlines blaring that Clinton blames Sanders for what happened 10 months ago will reopen old wounds and undermine those efforts, making Democrats look nearly as fractured as Republicans.\u000a\u000aWhat the party needs at this moment is to look forward, not back.\u000a\u000aAnd if party politics weren\u2019t enough of a headache, the timing of the book release is also problematic from a news-cycle perspective. While the decision on when to release a manuscript is often made months in advance, the release date for this one means that Clinton will start her promotional rounds on television this weekend, just as Hurricane Irma is set to land in Florida. Not exactly the publicity storm she\u2019ll be looking for.
