aVIntel's new Dual-Core Xeon Processor 5100 | Intel via Getty Images Intel wins retrial over \u20ac1.06 billion fine in setback for Commission Ruling translates into years of additional litigation and casts doubt over landmark Commission case.\u000a\u000aIn a victory for Intel\u2019s lawyers, the EU\u2019s top court on Wednesday ordered a retrial of the chipmaker\u2019s appeal against a \u20ac1.06 billion antitrust fine, ruling that a lower court should have delved further into the European Commission accusations.\u000a\u000aThe ruling translates into years of additional litigation and casts doubt over a landmark Commission case.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe General Court was required to examine all of Intel\u2019s arguments \u2026 which the General Court failed to do,\u201d the European Court of Justice said in a statement issued to the press.\u000a\u000aCommission regulators concluded in 2009 that Intel, then the dominant manufacturer of certain computer chips, offered discounts or paid customers on condition they shun rival Advanced Micro Devices. It was fined \u20ac1.06 billion, a record sum until the Commission hit Google with a \u20ac2.42 billion sanction in June.\u000a\u000aThe General Court had backed the Commission and rejected Intel\u2019s initial appeal in its entirety. The ECJ ruled it should have closely scrutinized the Commission\u2019s economic evidence but stopped well short of striking down the Commission decision.\u000a\u000aIn a blow for Intel, the ECJ rejected the chipmaker\u2019s claims that the EU antitrust regulator made procedural mistakes and targeted conduct outside the EU\u2019s jurisdiction.\u000a\u000aLawyers for Qualcomm, which is battling a probe based on similar allegations as contained in the Intel case, and Google, which is expected to file an appeal against the \u20ac2.42 billion fine in the coming week, will study the judgment closely.
