aVHungarian Pime Minister Viktor Orban gives a press conference in Budapest on July 4, 2017 | Attila Kisbendek/AFP via Getty Images Hungary: Visit by MEPs is \u2018political interference\u2019 Minister calls visit by committee \u2018outrageous.\u2019\u000a\u000aThe Hungarian government said a planned visit to the country by a group of MEPs later this month was \u201cpolitically motivated\u201d and would interfere with the country\u2019s general election, planned for spring 2018.\u000a\u000aIn an exchange of letters between the Hungarian government and Ingeborg Gräßle, the German MEP who chairs the European Parliament\u2019s Budgetary Control Committee, seen by POLITICO, János Lázár, the prime minister\u2019s chief of staff, asked the committee to \u201creconsider elements of the program,\u201d scheduled for September 16-18.\u000a\u000aMEPs on the committee, as well as advisers to the Parliament\u2019s political groups and representatives of the European Court of Auditors, plan to visit projects that have been given money from the bloc to \u201cverify if there are misuses of EU funds.\u201d\u000a\u000aIn a letter dated August 9, Lázár told Gräßle that the committee was not following Hungary\u2019s suggested list of projects to check and asked its members to follow a \u201cbalanced program\u201d not a \u201cstrongly politically motivated one.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI found it outrageous that a committee of the European Parliament systematically ignores and rejects a notable amount of the suggestions of the Hungarian government, thus significantly interferes in the Hungarian [election] campaign,\u201d he wrote.\u000a\u000aHe said the aim of the visit was \u201cnot to learn about the implementation of the [EU\u2019s] cohesion policy in Hungary, but to comply with the aims of the Hungarian political opposition, which I categorically reject.\u201d\u000a\u000aLázár also criticized a lack of visits to \u201ctowns currently lead by opposition party politicians,\u201d while a visit to the home village of the Prime Minister Viktor Orbán is on the agenda.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe program was agreed by all groups,\u201d Gräßle said. \u201cTwo groups \u2014 the EPP and Greens\u2014\u2013 gave input on projects. All other projects were proposed by the secretariat of our committee, and agreed by all groups as well.\u000a\u000a\u201cI would like to reassure the Hungarian government once again that there is no bias neither behind the choice of the date of our mission, nor of the projects. The Budgetary Control Committee will conduct its visit in a politically neutral way, as we always do.\u201d\u000a\u000aGreen MEP Judith Sargentini said the Hungarian response was surprising.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhat struck me most is the lack of diplomatic language in the letters,\u201d Sargentini said. She said she understands that the government might not be supportive of what is essentially an audit, but she expected \u201ca neutral approach,\u201d to the committee visit.\u000a\u000aGräßle asked European Parliament President Antonio Tajani to raise the issue with Jean-Claude Juncker, the president of the European Commission.\u000a\u000aShe said the \u201clack of cooperation\u201d from the Hungarians and their suggestion to change the agenda of the visit was \u201csufficiently serious\u201d for the Commission to discuss it.
