aVBritish Shadow Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union Keir Starmer arrives at the BBC | Andy Rain/EPA Labour to Tories: Help us stop Brexit power grab Keir Starmer says there are several Tories with \u2018pretty fundamental concerns\u2019 about the government\u2019s EU Withdrawal Bill plans.\u000a\u000aLONDON \u2014 Conservative MPs should vote with Labour \u201cin the public interest\u201d to stop the government using Brexit to adopt sweeping new powers to change the law without consulting parliament, according to the opposition\u2019s Brexit spokesman.\u000a\u000aWith the government\u2019s EU Withdrawal Bill to be debated by MPs Thursday, Labour\u2019s Keir Starmer said there were several Tories who had \u201cpretty fundamental concerns\u201d about the government\u2019s plans and urged them to vote with Labour to amend the bill.\u000a\u000aThe bill is designed to absorb many thousands of EU rules and regulations into British law in order to avoid regulatory blackholes when the U.K. leaves the European Union in March 2019. The Department for Exiting the European Union has said there is not enough time to get what it sees as necessary \u201ccorrections\u201d through the House of Commons and so will use so-called Henry VIII clauses to speed up the process by allowing ministers to amend regulation without giving MPs to vote on changes.\u000a\u000aStarmer told POLITICO: \u201cTo pour this sort of power into the hands of ministers is objectionable. It\u2019s as wide a bill \u2026 as I\u2019ve ever seen, and I\u2019m sure there are Tory MPs who think the same way.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe question really for Tory MPs is in what circumstances they will either amend [the bill] themselves or vote for our amendments. I hope they do. It\u2019s in the public interest that they do.\u201d\u000a\u000aSome senior Conservatives have already broken ranks over the Withdrawal Bill. Dominic Grieve, a former attorney general, said in an article in the Evening Standard Wednesday that it risked seeing \u201cour domestic constitution and liberties vandalized.\u201d The chair of the influential treasury committee, Nicky Morgan, also spoke out against the bill, and former Business Minister Anna Soubry warned Theresa May in the House of Commons Wednesday that the bill could represent an \u201cunprecedented and unnecessary government power grab.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhile Starmer is keen to reach out to Tory backbenchers, there are many in his own party who are concerned about Labour\u2019s new stance on Brexit.\u000a\u000aAsked whether he had reached out to potential Tory allies, Starmer was non-committal: \u201cThere are all sorts of discussions going on all the time in this place,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aThe Withdrawal Bill, formerly known as the Repeal Bill, will convert the bulk of EU law into U.K. legislation to avoid disruption on Brexit day.\u000a\u000aThe bill will begin its second reading Thursday, with MPs voting on it on Monday. It is likely that any major amendments will be put forward during the bill\u2019s committee stage, which comes after Monday\u2019s vote.\u000a\u000aWhile Starmer is keen to reach out to Tory backbenchers, there are many in his own party who are concerned about Labour\u2019s new stance on Brexit. The party now backs a transition arrangement, keeping the U.K. in the single market and a customs union for \u201cas long as is necessary.\u201d\u000a\u000aThree Labour MPs from northern constituencies where a majority of people voted for Brexit, who did not want to be named, said they are deeply concerned about the perception they are trying to \u201cblock Brexit\u201d by voting against the bill. One said they may defy Jeremy Corbyn\u2019s orders and abstain.\u000a\u000aA senior party official confirmed there was \u201cmuch nervousness\u201d among some Labour MPs who have \u201cconcerns on how it will look\u201d to vote against the bill. The official said mass abstentions on the Labour benches were \u201cpossible.\u201d\u000a\u000aStarmer said that while he understood the concerns of some Labour MPs, the party\u2019s position remained clear \u2014 that the U.K. would be leaving the EU come what may. He also ruled out a second referendum during the transition period, and set Labour against any post-transition deal that saw the U.K. stay in the single market but without a say in its rules.\u000a\u000a\u201cI think he [Davis] is right to challenge [the EU], he is right, as any government would, to seek to ensure the sum is as low as possible\u201d \u2014 Keir Starmer\u000a\u000a\u201cI understand why different MPs coming from different perspectives and from different constituencies have the concerns they have,\u201d he said. \u201cWe have made every effort to take on board the views across the PLP [Parliamentary Labour Party].\u201d\u000a\u000aStarmer, who will take on David Davis in the debates over the Withdrawal Bill, has criticized the Brexit secretary for his handling of the negotiations with Brussels.\u000a\u000aHowever, one area where Labour\u2019s stance chimes with the government\u2019s is on the so-called Brexit bill \u2014 the U.K.\u2019s financial obligations to the EU upon exit. Starmer said a Labour government would also fight to keep the bill as low as possible.\u000a\u000a\u201cI think he [Davis] is right to challenge [the EU], he is right, as any government would, to seek to ensure the sum is as low as possible,\u201d Starmer said.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s important to agree the principles but I don\u2019t think it\u2019s possible to put a sum on it at the moment and I have not criticized David Davis for having done so.\u201d
