aVBelgian authorities are trying to stop cocaine smuggling in the port of Antwerp | Mark Renders/Getty Images Euro-press review Belgium\u2019s cocaine problem Macron\u2019s Greek visit, Hurricane Irma and British government squabbles on Europe\u2019s front pages.\u000a\u000aFrance\u000a\u000aFrench front pages focused on the damage caused by Hurricane Irma in France\u2019s overseas territories. At least 12 people died in the Caribbean and dozens were injured. The French islands of Saint-Martin and Saint-Barthélemy were particularly affected, according to the report. Le Figaro covered the French president\u2019s state visit to Greece Thursday on its front page. \u201cIn Athens, Emmanuel Macron wants to rebuild Europe,\u201d the paper wrote. Macron called for solidarity and for all EU countries to debate a new common European project.\u000a\u000aUnited Kingdom\u000a\u000aThe Guardian wrote about a call by Labour MP David Lammy to tackle the \u201cracial bias\u201d in the British criminal justice system. In a report, Lammy called for prosecutions against some black and minority ethnic suspects to be be deferred or dropped to help tackle the bias against them.\u000a\u000aBritish papers also covered Irma on their front pages, with the Times reporting the U.K. had been criticized for delays in sending help to affected islands. Pro-Remain Conservative MPs have urged Theresa May to sack a minister and a Treasury aide, who were accused of supporting a letter designed to lock the prime minister into a hard Brexit, the Times also reported.\u000a\u000aGermany\u000a\u000aDiesel summits will not solve the car emissions crisis, Baden-Württemberg\u2019s Prime Minister Winfried Kretschmann said in an interview with FAZ. Die Welt reported on Germans losing their patience with Turkey, with a record 84 percent opposed to the country joining the EU in a Deutschlandtrend survey. In the same survey, 77 percent said they wanted the federal government to impose economic sanctions on Ankara.\u000a\u000aSecurity experts have found serious deficiencies in software to be used in Germany\u2019s upcoming federal election, Die Welt wrote. The software, which collects results in municipalities and transfers them to regional offices, was not secured by encryption or authentication. The manufacturer is working on updates, according to the report.\u000a\u000aBelgium\u000a\u000aBelgian police are preparing an action plan to tackle record-level cocaine smuggling in the port of Antwerp, according to De Standaard. Some 30,000 kilograms of cocaine was seized in 2016, up from just under 5,000 kilograms in 2013. Police fear the sharp increase in violent crime in Antwerp is linked to drug crime and cocaine trafficking.\u000a\u000aA survey published in Le Soir suggested the social-liberal Défi party will be the biggest winner from the ongoing political crisis in the French-speaking part of Belgium. Support for the party has doubled since March: If elections were held today, it would receive 18.4 percent of the vote, up from 9.3 percent. Défi leader Olivier Maingain emerged as the most popular politician in the capital. Support for the Socialists has fallen amid a series of scandals to 12.1 percent from 18.1 percent.
