aVSpanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy says he "will do whatever is needed without relinquishing anything, to prevent\u201d the Catalan independence referendum | Pierre-Philippe Marcou/AFP via Getty Images Mariano Rajoy on Catalonia: \u2018There won\u2019t be a referendum\u2019 Spain\u2019s PM warns Catalan officials not to \u2018underestimate the strength of Spanish democracy.\u2019\u000a\u000aMADRID \u2014 Mariano Rajoy on Thursday unleashed the full power of the Spanish legal system against Catalan leaders\u2019 plans to hold a binding referendum on independence on October 1.\u000a\u000aThe Spanish government went to the Constitutional Court to challenge the Catalan government\u2019s decision on Wednesday evening to call the vote.\u000a\u000aMadrid asked the court to provisionally suspend the referendum law approved by the Catalan parliament and all the measures taken by the Catalan cabinet, and to urge every member of the regional government, all the mayors in Catalonia and other officials to comply with the decision. The Constitutional Court has the power to force officials to comply with its decisions and can suspend them from office if they refuse to do so.\u000a\u000aLate Thursday, the Constitutional Court decided to proceed with the government\u2019s appeal, suspend the referendum bill and all related measures, and warn officials of their duty to comply with its decision.\u000a\u000a\u201cThere won\u2019t be a self-determination referendum,\u201d Rajoy told reporters. \u201cI will do whatever is needed, without relinquishing anything, to prevent it.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cWe all decide together about what belongs to all of us, which is our country,\u201d he added, warning Catalan officials not to \u201cunderestimate the strength of Spanish democracy.\u201d\u000a\u000aAt the same time, Spain\u2019s public prosecutor announced he was launching criminal actions against the entire Catalan cabinet and regional lawmakers involved in processing the referendum bill. The prosecutor also urged the police to watch out for referendum-related activities, with local media reporting that a printer in Tarragona was raided on suspicion that ballot papers were being made.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, the Catalan government led by Carles Puigdemont sent a letter to all city halls asking for help setting up the vote. Some mayors expressed support publicly despite a letter being sent by the Spanish government to all public servants in Catalonia warning them that the planned referendum is illegal and asking them to disregard Puigdemont\u2019s request for support.\u000a\u000aThe Catalan chamber on Thursday started to debate a law on a transition period following a successful independence vote. If approved, its legality would almost certainly be challenged by Madrid.
