aVEnd of an era at Vanity Fair -- Spicer to late night -- Local media teams up for Irma\u000a\u000aWith Cristiano Lima\u000a\u000aEND OF AN ERA: Graydon Carter, the longtime editor of Vanity Fair, and longtime nemesis of President Donald Trump, is retiring at the end of the year. Carter, who has led the Condé Nast magazine for 25 years, said in an official announcement that he intends to pursue a \u201cthird act.\u201d He\u2019ll stick around long enough to oversee the magazine\u2019s 2018 Hollywood issue. His influence on popular culture is hard to overstate. Between revealing the identity of \u201cDeep Throat,\u201d and iconic covers featuring Demi Moore and Caitlyn Jenner, among many other accomplishments Carter\u2019s journalistic legacy is secure. Carter also understood the value of hospitality. His New York restaurants The Waverly Inn and The Monkey Bar remain hotspots, and Vanity Fair\u2019s Oscars party and White House Correspondents\u2019 Association Dinner afterparty have long been the hottest tickets in Los Angeles and D.C.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000a\u2014The New York Times has an interview with Carter, including more on this \u201cthird act.\u201d \u201cHe has \u2018the rough architecture\u2019 of a future project in mind, perhaps involving new forms of storytelling, but he demurred on the details. \u2018I\u2019m not a big announcer,\u2019 Mr. Carter said, tortoiseshell glasses in hand. \u2018Best to fail quietly at the beginning of something rather than make grand pronouncements.\u2019\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014So who could replace him? There are a few names that have long been mentioned, most notably Janice Min, who is currently co-president of The Hollywood Reporter-Billboard Media Group, and who previously led US Weekly. New York magazine\u2019s Adam Moss and former Cosmopolitan editor-in-chief Joanna Coles have also been mentioned.\u000a\u000a\u2014Then there is President Donald Trump. Carter has antagonized Trump since the 1980s, when, at Spy magazine, he referred to the then-real estate developer as a \u201cshort-fingered vulgarian.\u201d That line remained a sore spot for Trump, who made Carter a regular target of his tweets over the years. Spy also memorably pranked Trump by sending checks with smaller and smaller donations to New York\u2019s wealthiest, to see who would bother cashing them. Trump cashed a check for 13 cents. After his election, Trump traveled to One World Trade Center, where he held court with Condé Nast executives, including Carter, who did not sound thrilled to be there.\u000a\u000a\u2014Carter and Vanity Fair even squeezed in one final joke, at Trump\u2019s expense. In the press release announcing his retirement, his biography included this line: \u201cIn 1986, he founded, with Kurt Andersen and Tom Phillips, Spy magazine, the satirical monthly whose voice, style, and design remain influential to this day, and whose articles played a large hand in fingering the era\u2019s villains and their shortcomings.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a** A message from Service Year Alliance: Hundreds of dinosaurs rallied at the Capitol to tell Congress to stop national service extinction. President Trump\u2019s budget proposes the elimination of national service programs like AmeriCorps. These dinosaurs have a clear message for Congress: Stop National Service Extinction and Let Us Serve. Learn more at LetUsServe.org. **\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aGood morning and welcome back to Morning Media. I always want to improve Morning Media and make it more useful to you, so please send me tips, ideas and feedback! I\u2019m on Twitter @alexweprin and on email at alexweprin@gmail.com. Morning Media is produced with help from Cristiano Lima (clima@politico.com / @ludacristiano). Archives. Subscribe.\u000a\u000aINTERVIEW SEASON: Keep your eyes glued to your TV sets, as a number of high-profile interviews will be happening over the next few weeks.\u000a\u000a\u2014Sean Spicer is hitting his first late night couch since departing the White House. Spicer will appear on ABC\u2019s \u201cJimmy Kimmel Live\u201d next Wednesday, the show announced Thursday. (Related: Fox News says it won\u2019t be offering Spicer a contributor contract, meaning that he won\u2019t be striking a deal with them or CNN).\u000a\u000a\u2014President Trump appears to be willing to grant an interview to a cable news journalist, rather than a pundit on a program like \u201cFox & Friends.\u201d Fox News anchor Bret Baier told The Hollywood Reporter's Jeremy Barr the White House is \u201ctrying to find a date that works, and we're obviously amicable to whatever they come up with\u2026 So hopefully it's going to come together here in the next couple of weeks."\u000a\u000a\u2014The Hillary Clinton book tour continues. After \u201cCBS Sunday Morning\u201d this weekend, and ABC\u2019s \u201cThe View\u201d next Wednesday, Clinton will appear on CBS\u2019 \u201cLate Show with Stephen Colbert\u201d Sept. 19.\u000a\u000a\u2014The first excerpts from Steve Bannon\u2019s \u201c60 Minutes\u201d interview are online . Bannon accused the Catholic church of being pro-immigration for purely economic reasons, and declares the he is going to war with the Republican establishment.\u000a\u000aTHE NEXT DAY FACEBOOK-RUSSIA BACKLASH: After self-reporting that Russian-tied accounts spent some $150,000 on more than 5,200 political ads last year on their network , Facebook is facing increased scrutiny for its handling of misleading and targeted information online. "I think we may just be seeing the tip of the iceberg,\u201d said Mark Warner, the vice chairman of the Senate Intelligence Committee, of their disclosure.\u000a\u000a\u2014As the Washington Post\u2019s Matea Gold points out, the matter is quickly raising questions of whether increased regulation may be needed to monitor how the private social media giants handle such political advertising money, and whether Facebook\u2019s actions in selling the ads may have breached elections laws. And as new POLITICO media reporter Jason Schwartz highlights , the controversy is doing little to quell concerns over their internal efforts to combat fake news.\u000a\u000aMUST READS:\u000a\u000a\u2014On a happy note, this touching profile of Harvey and Irma Schluter, a couple married 75 years who happen to share names with two massive hurricanes.\u000a\u000a\u2014On an unsettling note, this dispatch from Pyongyang, North Korea, filed ny The New Yorker\u2019s Evan Osnos.\u000a\u000aLOCAL MEDIA TEAMS UP TO TACKLE IRMA. As Hurricane Irma approaches Florida, local media outlets are stepping up to the challenge to cover the historic storm. In South Florida, public radio affiliate WLRN and news site The New Tropic are pooling resources to provide readers information on where to find shelter, and how to assess damage after Irma\u2019s landfall, in a timely merger of new media and legacy media. Meanwhile, venerable print publications like The Miami Herald, The Orlando Sentinel and others are lowering their paywalls to provide its readers with temporary access to all its coverage of the storm, following in the footsteps of national outlets like The New York Times, The Washington Post and the Wall Street Journal during their Hurricane Harvey coverage.\u000a\u000aSTUDY: INTERNET CLOSING IN ON TV AS MAIN NEWS SOURCE: A new Pew study suggests that TV\u2019s long stranglehold on news consumers continues to deteriorate, as online news sources take up more and more of the consumer\u2019s time. \u201cAs of August, 43% of Americans report often getting news online, just 7 percentage points lower than the 50% who often get news on television, according to a Pew Research Center survey conducted in August. This gap between the two news platforms was 19 points in early 2016, more than twice as large.\u201d\u000a\u000aREVOLVING DOOR:\u000a\u000a\u2014Morning Media has learned that Brian Flood, most recently a media reporter for The Wrap, will be joining Foxnews.com to cover the media beat as part of the site\u2019s digital expansion. He\u2019ll start next week.\u000a\u000a\u2014USA Today has named Wendy Benjaminson managing editor for government and politics. Benjaminson was most recently national editor at the AP. She succeeds Lee Horwich who becomes managing editor for national enterprise.\u000a\u000a\u2014The New York Times has named Deborah Solomon economics editor in its D.C. bureau. Solomon previously worked at The Wall Street Journal, where she oversaw the financial regulatory and law enforcement teams.\u000a\u000a\u2014The Atlantic\u2019s Molly Ball is now a CNN political analyst. Bloomberg White House correspondent Margaret Talev is also now a CNN political analyst.\u000a\u000aTHE GLOBAL POLICY LAB: POLITICO Europe is launching Global Policy Lab, a first-of-its kind experiment in collaborative journalism that is expected to produce new policy solutions and inform the public debate on key issues. POLITICO readers are among the most engaged and educated in the world, and the Global Policy Lab will tap into their experience and knowledge to develop solutions to pressing challenges. POLITICO is partnering with GE on the first installment, titled Engineering Growth, to look at the rise of digital manufacturing in Germany, Europe\u2019s largest economy, and explore ways to improve the economies of France and the United Kingdom. GET INVOLVED: Sign up to the weekly newsletter HERE.\u000a\u000aSOUNDBITE: \u201cThere's a connection, people, between those polls about trust in the media reaching new lows and online disinformation campaigns succeeding.\u201d \u2014NYU journalism professor Jay Rosen .\u000a\u000aEXTRAS:\u000a\u000a\u2014The first promo for Megyn Kelly\u2019s new morning show debuted on NBC\u2019s \u201cThursday Night Football.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u2014AT&T executive John Stankey reiterated on Thursday that the company does not plan to sell CNN once it closes its acquisition of Time Warner. "They've got wonderful content that's time and place specific, that's time-of-day specific, that can engage audiences in real time," he said.\u000a\u000a\u2014Charles Harder, the lawyer who sued Gawker into bankruptcy, is now targeting Gawker\u2019s former sister site Jezebel.\u000a\u000a\u2014Movie studios blame the website Rotten Tomatoes for the poor performance of this summer\u2019s box office.\u000a\u000a\u2014U.S. media stocks, including Disney, collapsed as concerns over digital disruption spread.\u000a\u000a\u2014Rich Lowry\u2019s message to President Trump: please turn off the TV.\u000a\u000a\u2014The student government association at Duquesne University tried to block the school paper from reporting budget information.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a** A message from Service Year Alliance: 80,000 young people serve every year with AmeriCorps, the Peace Corps, and YouthBuild. They\u2019re fighting the opioid epidemic, supporting our veterans, teaching in underperforming schools, and responding to natural disasters. In fact, hundreds of AmeriCorps members are already on the ground in Texas helping respond after Hurricane Harvey. If President Trump\u2019s budget becomes reality, national service programs like AmeriCorps will go extinct. Service Year Alliance and hundreds of national service supporters dressed as dinosaurs rallied at the Capitol to stop national service extinction and tell Congress to Let Us Serve. Learn more at LetUsServe.org. **
