aVSALZGITTER, Germany \u2014 Sometimes it\u2019s better to be the supporting actor than the main star.\u000a\u000aThat\u2019s something Sigmar Gabriel, Germany\u2019s foreign minister, has proved since stepping down as leader of the Social Democrats (SPD) and handing the job \u2014 and the chance to challenge Angela Merkel for the chancellorship \u2014 to former European Parliament President Martin Schulz.\u000a\u000aWhile Schulz is struggling to make headway in his campaign to oust Merkel in this month\u2019s general election, Gabriel is enjoying an extraordinary resurgence in popularity. That turnaround puts him in a strong position to be the more influential of the two if the SPD ends up reprising its current role as junior partner to Merkel\u2019s conservatives after the election.\u000a\u000aAs part of a reshuffle of roles among senior Social Democrats in late January, Gabriel announced he was giving up the party leadership, wouldn\u2019t run for chancellor and would switch from economy minister to foreign minister. At the time, that looked like a humiliation for him, with the foreign ministry something of a consolation prize.\u000a\u000aIn his new job, however, the combative 57-year-old has thrived, making headlines every other day with bold statements on Turkey, U.S. President Donald Trump and Russia \u2014 as well as on issues only loosely related to foreign policy such as the German car industry.\u000a\u000aGabriel\u2019s newfound popularity and high profile have irritated some SPD officials.\u000a\u000a\u201cI like to say Angela Merkel is a good chancellor, as long as the SPD takes care of her\u201d \u2014 Sigmar Gabriel\u000a\u000aWhile some high-ranking party officials said Gabriel is just doing his job as Germany\u2019s top diplomat \u2014 \u201cand doing it well,\u201d as one said \u2014 others believe he is preparing the ground to secure his own political future after the September 24 election.\u000a\u000a\u201cHe\u2019s just warming up,\u201d said a party official in the Bundestag, speaking on condition of anonymity.\u000a\u000aGabriel country\u000a\u000aA couple of weeks ago, Gabriel began \u2014 to the surprise of many \u2014 to point increasingly to what the SPD achieved in government with Merkel\u2019s conservatives during the last four years.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe achieved a lot, although the SPD only scored 26 percent and Merkel\u2019s conservatives more than 40 percent of the votes [in the 2013 election],\u201d Gabriel told a campaign rally last week in a market square in his parliamentary constituency of Salzgitter, as the audience, sipping on beer and munching bratwurst, waited for Schulz to arrive.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe were lucky that Merkel primarily wanted to become chancellor and otherwise left it to us to make policy,\u201d he added. \u201cI like to say Angela Merkel is a good chancellor, as long as the SPD takes care of her.\u201d\u000a\u000aHis underlying message seemed to be: More of the same wouldn\u2019t be so bad. It triggered applause in Salzgitter, a community of 31 villages and towns divided by fields and factories.\u000a\u000aBut Schulz has been trying to strike a different note \u2014 suggesting he would prefer his party did not spend another four years in Merkel\u2019s shadow.\u000a\u000aAfter Schulz arrived and took the stage, he was at pains to stress how warm his relationship with Gabriel is. He opened by saying that Salzgitter was the right place \u201cto make clear that something exists in politics which many people deny: the friendship between two men who carry responsibility for the SPD.\u201d\u000a\u000aBut, perhaps in jest, he also offered a less than ringing endorsement of Gabriel\u2019s presence at the rally.\u000a\u000a\u201cI\u2019m particularly glad that he sits here in the first row,\u201d he said, \u201cand that he supports me and won\u2019t interrupt me with interjections during my speech.\u201d\u000a\u000aFrom the moment he became the party\u2019s nominee for chancellor, Schulz accepted he would sometimes not be able to predict Gabriel\u2019s actions, according to an SPD official close to the candidate. But Schulz has become increasingly irritated by some of Gabriel\u2019s recent statements, including his explicit embrace of the past \u201cgrand coalition\u201d with Merkel, the official said.\u000a\u000a\u2018Kamikaze candidate\u2019 to comeback kid\u000a\u000aWhen Gabriel announced in January that he would not be the SPD\u2019s candidate for chancellor, he described the move as a \u201cservice to his party\u201d and did not hide the fact that it was difficult for him.\u000a\u000aFor more than seven years, Gabriel \u2014 a Social Democrat to his core who says he went into politics as a reaction to the Nazi ideologies of his father \u2014 had toiled as party chief, trying to drag Germany\u2019s oldest party from the worst crisis of its history.\u000a\u000aDuring that time, he became the party\u2019s scapegoat for essentially everything that went wrong. Particularly after he took over the economy ministry in 2013, he struggled to reconcile the wishes of his crisis-ridden party with policy decisions he had to make as a minister \u2014 sometimes alienating the left of the SPD, at other times frustrating centrists.\u000a\u000aHis popularity fell so low that the idea of him running for chancellor prompted party officials in the parliament to christen him the \u201ckamikaze candidate.\u201d\u000a\u000aYet just seven months later, Gabriel has risen to become Germany\u2019s third most-popular politician \u2014 behind only Merkel and Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble, and significantly ahead of Schulz, in seventh place, according to a recent survey by pollsters Forschungsgruppe Wahlen.\u000a\u000aAlthough whoever occupies the foreign ministry is usually relatively popular, this ascent is remarkable \u2014 particularly as it happened at the same time as his party lost support, after an initial bounce when Schulz was announced as the candidate for chancellor.\u000a\u000a\u201cGermany remains a power of peace in Europe and not an armed power\u201d \u2014 Sigmar Gabriel\u000a\u000aGabriel also appears to have undergone something of a personal transformation. He has lost a significant amount of weight and now comes over as less aggressive and more humorous in media interviews, speaking appreciatively about how he gets to spend entire weekends with his young daughters.\u000a\u000aPeace push\u000a\u000aHe has also campaigned heavily on a theme that seems close to his heart, railing against the idea that Germany should almost double its military spending to 2 percent of GDP to conform to a NATO guideline \u2014 and the demands of Donald Trump.\u000a\u000a\u201cGermany remains a power of peace in Europe and not an armed power,\u201d Gabriel said in Salzgitter, as the crowd burst into applause.\u000a\u000aSuch issues fall into his portfolio as foreign minister, but opinions inside the SPD differ over whether his prominent role is helping the party in the campaign.\u000a\u000aWhile some argue that Gabriel helps boost the SPD\u2019s standing, others fear his visibility draws attention away from Schulz and overshadows some of the candidate\u2019s attempts to make waves.\u000a\u000aPrivately, officials caution that, when it comes to his own political career, Gabriel has little to gain from a Schulz victory.\u000a\u000aIf Schulz, against all expectations, somehow manages to turn the tide at the last minute and become chancellor, Gabriel\u2019s prestigious office of foreign minister would most likely go to a coalition partner.\u000a\u000aThings will look different, however, if Germany ends up with another grand coalition between Merkel\u2019s conservatives and the SPD as their junior partner. The foreign office would then most likely remain in the hands of the Social Democrats.\u000a\u000a\u201cAnd who do you think the SPD would want to see in the foreign office?\u201d one SPD official asked. \u201cA failed candidate \u2014 or someone who voluntarily stepped down from being party chief for the sake of the party?\u201d
