aVJean-Claude Juncker risks going down in history as the man who lost Britain. He now has two years to become the man who charted the path forward for Europe instead.\u000a\u000aSpeaking in an extended interview last month at his office in the Berlaymont, the president of the European Commission laid out his thoughts for the year ahead, including his intention to use his State of the European Union speech next week to push for greater EU integration \u2014 without losing less enthusiastic Eastern European countries.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhile I am not an integration fanatic, I am very much in favor of deepening the European Union and at the same time respecting to the fullest extent justified, national interests,\u201d he said. He excluded treaty changes in the short term, \u201ceven though they would be necessary\u201d down the line.\u000a\u000aOnce disparaged as the tippling captain of a sinking ship, Juncker said that he, like the EU, is on an upswing, with populism on the wane (for now), Brexit negotiations under control and the bloc\u2019s economy on a slow but steady incline. The sentiment is captured by the theme he has chosen for his yearly agenda-setting speech: \u201cSailing with the wind!\u201d\u000a\u000aIt is a dramatic turnaround of fortunes for the bloc and its president. A year ago, both were written off by many.\u000a\u000aYet as Juncker now pushes an ambitious vision that touches on many areas of the EU, from the economy to security, his track record in three years in office offers reasons for skepticism about his chances of success. His tenure has been marked by at least as many lows as highs, from Brexit and the migration crisis to barely contained complaints about his personal health and remote management style.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe 2017 speech is indeed more important than the 2018 one. So, I think about delivering my own view on things\u201d \u2014 Jean-Claude Juncker\u000a\u000aHaving declared his tenure a \u201clast chance\u201d for Europe and himself as the head of a \u201cpolitical Commission,\u201d the former prime minister of Luxembourg hasn\u2019t restored the office to the heights of influence last seen in Jacques Delors\u2019 tenure in Brussels more than 20 years ago. Whereas then the institution\u2019s power of initiative was unquestioned, any current occupant must grapple with the reality of empowered national capitals, none more so than Berlin, and skepticism about Europe\u2019s ability to provide the answers to peoples\u2019 problems.\u000a\u000aBut Juncker is the ultimate survivor, a politician who has worked the frontlines of power on the Continent over three decades. He\u2019s in the home stretch of what he says is his first and last term in Brussels, and presumably his final job in politics. Even detractors within the Berlaymont \u2014 who sometimes bristle at being left out of a small circle of decision-makers composed of Juncker and his closest aide, Martin Selmayr \u2014 have noted a reenergized swing in the president\u2019s step.\u000a\u000a\u2018Personal manifesto\u2019\u000a\u000aJuncker\u2019s proposals, to be pursued in his final, full work-year before the 2019 European election, will include expanded military cooperation, concerted action on trade and trade defense, and the transformation of the European Stability Mechanism into a permanent safety net to protect not just national budgets but the pocketbooks and quality of life of the bloc\u2019s citizens.\u000a\u000aMost important, for Juncker\u2019s legacy at least, the speech is his last chance to lay the ground for being remembered as the Commission president who healed the bleeding wound caused by the first ever exit of an EU country.\u000a\u000aChatter has begun about who will replace him in 2019, and little to no policymaking is expected to take place between the European parliamentary election in May or June 2019 and the end of Juncker\u2019s term that fall.\u000a\u000aJuncker called next week\u2019s State of the Union substantively more important than next year\u2019s address, which will serve as a valedictory one and as a call to arms for his successor, but less as a policy blueprint.\u000a\u000aThe initiatives Juncker unveils will offer a window into his preferences for the EU\u2019s future \u2014 a debate he and his College of Commissioners kick-started in a \u201cwhite paper\u201d earlier this year. While the white paper laid out five potential pathways for Europe, Juncker\u2019s speech will in many ways serve as a roadmap for the so-called sixth scenario that he has hinted at in recent days.\u000a\u000aJuncker told POLITICO that he has spent the past months consulting governments, national parliaments, unions and trade associations, and his commissioners, but that said, he is inclined to use the address in Strasbourg as a personal manifesto. So the advice he received from his commissioners at an annual retreat last week will not necessarily be adopted, which critics would note would be far from the first time that has happened.\u000a\u000a\u201cI\u2019m asking myself if I shouldn\u2019t take the opportunity to say what I myself am thinking,\u201d he said. \u201cThe 2017 speech is indeed more important than the 2018 one. So, I think about delivering my own view on things.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhat he envisions is an EU where decision-making is streamlined, allowing the bloc to act more nimbly in areas where greater cooperation is needed and desired, while also drawing bright lines around areas of national sovereignty where he believes the capitals are right to demand their due deference.\u000a\u000aThe chalice Juncker is reaching for is balance. An underwhelming speech might consign him as the Brexit-only president; overly bold proposals risk being blocked by the more cautious EU countries (and ambition stops easily where money is involved).\u000a\u000a\u201cThere\u2019s a window of opportunity,\u201d said Selmayr, Juncker\u2019s chief of staff. And when there is, \u201cyou can make two mistakes: overshoot or undershoot.\u201d\u000a\u000aEast-West divide\u000a\u000aJuncker, who served 19 years as Luxembourg\u2019s prime minister before taking the helm in Brussels, is seeking to take full advantage of this moment to push his ideas \u2014 but he\u2019s also aware of the need to navigate the shoals of national interest.\u000a\u000aOn Tuesday, Polish President Andrzej Duda warned sharply against pushing for deeper integration while others hold back, a concept known as a \u201cmultispeed Europe.\u201d Such a move, Duda warned, could break up the bloc.\u000a\u000aCriticized for ignoring and almost never visiting the Eastern EU states, Juncker insisted he was aware of the need to balance their desires with those of older, Western members of the club. \u201cThis weighs on my thinking and doing, because I always have to ask myself: If I propose this or that, then I immediately have a difference between East and West,\u201d he said. \u201cThat\u2019s a topic for the future that we need to tackle right now. I put a lot of effort into [talking to Slovakian Prime Minister Robert] Fico and [Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor] Orbán.\u201d\u000a\u000aHe said he made less of an effort with the Polish government, with whom the Commission has been feuding over controversial reforms to the country\u2019s governance structure. Warsaw, he said, will be \u201cmore lonely after Brexit.\u201d\u000a\u000aOne country Juncker doesn\u2019t have to worry too much about is the United Kingdom. Longstanding British aversion to \u201can ever closer union\u201d was reflected in the U.K.\u2019s resistance to EU military integration and in its refusal to join the euro common currency zone.\u000a\u000aEurozone rising\u000a\u000aBrexit\u2019s silver lining, Juncker noted, is that without the U.K. it will be both far easier and far more necessary to better coordinate the bloc\u2019s fiscal policies and priorities.\u000a\u000a\u201cThere\u2019s a period of a happiness about the future in front of us, from now to March next year\u201d \u2014 Jean-Claude Juncker\u000a\u000a\u201cWhen the British leave, 85 percent of GDP comes from within the euro area,\u201d he said. \u201cIt is all the more urgent to ask how this monetary union can be accompanied by a stronger coordination of economic policy. This is actually the topic of a future European finance minister, who probably should rather be an economics minister rather than a finance minister.\u201d By pushing for someone from a traditionally less powerful ministry, Juncker signals that the role would be somewhat diminished, and focused on coordinating economic policies rather than telling national governments how much to spend or not.\u000a\u000aThe creation of an EU finance minister, which already has the crucial support of French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Angela Merkel, would further cement Juncker\u2019s legacy as a champion of the EU, and allow him to boast of fulfilling a major promise from his campaign for Commission president in 2014.\u000a\u000a\u201cBoth [Merkel and Macron] and everyone else must then agree on what the sphere of influence of a European finance minister can be,\u201d he said. \u201cIt will be so that this European finance minister won\u2019t be able nor [be] allowed to interfere in the sovereign right of national parliaments as regards the budget. You just have to figure it out.\u201d\u000a\u000aJuncker and his team also see an opportunity to press for the transformation of the European Stability Mechanism into a sort of European International Monetary Fund \u2014 ready to step in when an EU economy hits the rocks. That would allow the EU to declare victory in managing the financial hurricane that followed the 2008 financial crisis, and better prepare for similar events in the future.\u000a\u000aJuncker expressed particular gratification for the weaker-than-expected poll ratings of the far-right Alternative for Germany ahead of the German election on September 24, where Merkel is expected to win comfortably.\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s a \u201cstroke of luck,\u201d he said, that Germany\u2019s major parties \u2014 Merkel\u2019s Christian Democrats and former European Parliament President Martin Schulz\u2019s Social Democrats \u2014 \u201carticulate themselves clearly in pro-European way.\u201d\u000a\u000aA new Franco-German alliance \u2014 driven by Macron in France and Merkel in Germany \u2014 \u201cis undoubtedly a power plant for Europe,\u201d Juncker said, and an opportunity that should not be wasted. \u201cThere\u2019s a period of a happiness about the future in front of us, from now to March next year.\u201d
