aVThe EU\u2019s top competition enforcer could find her power to pursue antitrust cases severely curtailed come Wednesday if the European Commission loses a court battle with Intel.\u000a\u000aThe European Court of Justice is scheduled to publish its verdict in an appeal by Intel against a once-record \u20ac1.06 billion sanction. Though the court hasn\u2019t overturned a Commission judgment in almost 40 years, the U.S. chipmaker has some reason to hope for victory in this case: A senior member of the court last October lambasted the Commission and recommended its appeal be upheld.\u000a\u000aA judgment in Intel\u2019s favor will have a direct and immediate impact on Commissioner Margrethe Vestager\u2019s landmark antitrust probes into other American firms Qualcomm and Google, and it carries wider implications for Commission inquiries into dominant firms and cartels across the board.\u000a\u000aThe judgment could order the Commission to delve deeper into the economic logic behind each case, said Damien Geradin, a partner at Euclid Law. \u201cIt could be much more difficult to apply [competition rules] and there would be many more shades of gray.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe last time a Commission antitrust case against a dominant firm collapsed before the EU\u2019s top court was 1979.\u000a\u000aEnding the Commission\u2019s winning streak in court could also change the \u201cbalance of power\u201d between the Commission and defendants, resulting in fewer settlements and more court fights, he added.\u000a\u000aThe Commission declined to comment. Intel declined to comment.\u000a\u000aEagerly, very long awaited\u000a\u000aThe last time a Commission antitrust case against a dominant firm collapsed before the EU\u2019s top court was 1979.\u000a\u000aIn a sign of the Intel case\u2019s significance, senior Commission antitrust officials and competition lawyers are said to have cleared their agendas for Wednesday morning to read the ruling and map out its legal implications. The date of its delivery and the outcome has been the subject of unusually intense speculation in legal circles for months.\u000a\u000aThe verdict, in a case launched by one of Vestager\u2019s predecessors more than 10 years ago, comes as she enters the last two years of her mandate as Europe\u2019s commissioner for competition. Closing two open cases each against Google and Qualcomm will be critical for her legacy.\u000a\u000aVestager has been frustrated at the way competition probes drag out across years, but she is well aware of the importance of winning before the courts. \u201cFast is always better than slow, but best of all is to be just,\u201d she often says.\u000a\u000aCommission regulators in 2009 concluded that Intel, then the dominant manufacturer of certain computer chips, offered discounts or paid customers on the condition they shun rival Advanced Micro Devices. The Commission ruled such terms were illegal coming from a company that supplied 70 percent of the market for x86 CPUs, the main chip running PCs and laptops.\u000a\u000aThe case cemented the Commission\u2019s reputation as the world\u2019s foremost antitrust enforcer \u2014 U.S. enforcers hesitated to press a case and eventually settled after the company promised to change its contracts and paid $6.5 million \u2014 and emboldened it to pursue high-profile cases on its own.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe company was scathing of the Commission\u2019s case. At the time, Intel said the regulator \u201cignored or minimized \u2026 important evidence that contradicted its view of the world.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Intel precedent on the terms that a dominant firm can offer its customers is cited heavily in looming cases against Google\u2019s Android operating system for mobile and its AdSense for Search (AFS) advertising business, according to people familiar with the cases.\u000a\u000aIn the Android case, regulators take issue with a series of Google supply contracts that impose exclusivity on partners, from handset-makers to telecoms operators.\u000a\u000aIn the AFS case the Commission takes aim at terms in Google\u2019s advertising contracts that required websites to shun Google\u2019s rivals.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s a unique opportunity for the European Court of Justice to strike down the Commission decision and go against the old-fashioned approach of the Commission, in particular the legal service\u201d \u2014 Damien Geradin\u000a\u000aThe Intel precedent is also squarely at the center of one of the antitrust probes against Qualcomm, which alleges the U.S. chipmaker and technology firm made payments to Apple on condition it sourced chips exclusively from Qualcomm. After charging Qualcomm in December 2015, the case appears to be nearing an end.\u000a\u000aIntel\u2019s pushback\u000a\u000aIn its appeal, Intel accused the Commission of breaching its procedural rights by failing to properly report a meeting with Dell, where the latter is thought to have expressed reservations about the probe.\u000a\u000aCommission officials warned that requiring them to log each meeting would burden investigators with additional red tape and hamper their ability to gather intelligence. The court\u2019s verdict will be relevant for all ongoing probes and any ongoing appeals, including a likely action by Google against a \u20ac2.4 billion fine imposed in June against its Google Shopping service.\u000a\u000aA second line of attack in the Intel case focuses on how the contracts at issue were struck outside the EU. Investigators say they can pursue the deals because they affected competition with Europe.\u000a\u000aSuch disagreements come up \u201cquite often in cartel cases,\u201d said Oliver Geiss, a lawyer at Squire Patton Boggs.\u000a\u000aA third ground of appeal says the Commission cannot forbid dominant firms from handing out any discounts that involve exclusivity, but should draw on economics to show that a rebate hurt competition.\u000a\u000aInvestigators did model the economic effects of Intel\u2019s behavior, but the Commission\u2019s legal service has maintained in court that they did not need to: They point to case law dating back to the 1970s finding exclusivity rebates to be illegal when offered by a dominant firm.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s a unique opportunity for the European Court of Justice to strike down the Commission decision and go against the old-fashioned approach of the Commission, in particular the legal service,\u201d said Geradin, the lawyer.\u000a\u000aUPDATE: This article was updated to reflect that Intel declined to comment.
