aVBritish Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson says he is confident that a trade deal can be struck with the EU | Tolga Akmen/AFP via Getty Images Boris Johnson: EU legally bound to discuss trade relationship Foreign secretary has \u2018absolutely rock-solid confidence\u2019 that a deal will be struck with the EU.\u000a\u000aThe EU has a legal duty to discuss a future trade relationship with the U.K., Boris Johnson said Friday.\u000a\u000aBefore a meeting with his EU counterparts in Tallinn, the British foreign secretary told reporters that \u201cArticle 50 makes it very clear that the discussion about the exit for a country must be taken in the context of a discussion of the future arrangements, and that\u2019s what we are going to do,\u201d the Guardian reported.\u000a\u000aAccording to the EU, the terms of the split \u2014 citizens\u2019 rights, the exit bill and the Irish border \u2014 must be dealt with before talks can move on to trade. The Brits want trade talks on all issues to take place at the same time.\u000a\u000aJohnson said he had \u201cabsolutely rock-solid confidence\u201d that a deal would be struck with the EU. \u201cI think we can all work together to come up with a solution on that one. It is not beyond the wit of man,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aWhile in Estonia, Johnson visited British troops in the country as part of a NATO mission to deter Russian aggression in the region. He took a ride in a tank in full camouflage gear, which caused amusement back in London.\u000a\u000aThe Russian Embassy in the U.K. took to Twitter to mock the foreign secretary, writing: \u201c[Russian Foreign Minister] Sergey Lavrov doesn\u2019t need to ride a tank to make his point.\u000a\u000a\u201cHe\u2019d rather rely on consistency of message and evolving context.\u201d
