aVGerman Chancellor Angela Merkel may be losing older women in eastern Germany to the AfD | Sean Gallup/Getty Images euro-press review Merkel\u2019s \u2018forgotten sisters\u2019 French reforms, EU Brexit papers and Dutch Cabinet expansion feature on Thursday\u2019s front pages.\u000a\u000aGermany\u000a\u000aFAZ\u2019s front page featured an interview with Kostiantyn Yeliseyev, the foreign policy adviser to Ukraine\u2019s President Petro Poroshenko. Yeliseyev slammed German Foreign Minister Sigmar Gabriel\u2019s push to lift sanctions against Russia before Moscow fulfills its obligations under the Minsk Agreement as \u201cirresponsible,\u201d likening it to appeasing Hitler\u2019s Germany in 1938.\u000a\u000aThe paper also featured an election opinion poll conducted for FAZ. Angela Merkel\u2019s Christian Democrats polled at 38.5 percent, down 1 percentage point compared with two weeks ago, with Martin Schulz\u2019s Social Democrats in second place on 24 percent.\u000a\u000aTAZ reported on Merkel\u2019s \u201cforgotten sisters\u201d \u2014 older women living in the former East Germany whose salaries and living conditions are worst than those living in the West. These women are now considering voting for the far-right Alternative for Germany rather than Merkel\u2019s CDU in the federal election.\u000a\u000aUnited Kingdom\u000a\u000aThe Guardian\u2019s front page focused on leaked EU Brexit position papers, set to be published in the coming days. The Daily Telegraph also devoted front page real estate to the divorce, reporting that Prime Minister Theresa May\u2019s Brexit plans are in disarray, with senior party members Amber Rudd and Damian Green refusing to back plans to curb EU migration.\u000a\u000aThe Times reported on a crackdown on university staff pay, with institutions risking fines if they cannot justify why vice chancellors are paid more than the prime minister.\u000a\u000aFrance\u000a\u000aThe center-right Les Républicains are silent and \u201cwithout a strategy,\u201d failing to stand up to Emmanuel Macron, largely because they agree with much of the president\u2019s agenda, Le Figaro reported. Le Monde focused on the president\u2019s latest reform announcements, reporting on plans to shake up the railway sector to reduce its debt and to \u201cadjust\u201d France\u2019s external military operations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Netherlands\u000a\u000aDutch media focused on the devastation caused by Hurricane Irma in the Caribbean. De Telegraaf also reported on the composition of the new government: the Cabinet is expected to include 16 ministers, up from 13, with new ministers for climate, agriculture and food and immigration and integration. While the four possible coalition partners have not yet finished government formation talks, liberal Prime Minister Mark Rutte\u2019s new team is beginning to take shape, the paper wrote.\u000a\u000aAD featured a story on external staff members hired by government bodies, who often receive higher salaries than ministers. Ministries, provinces and municipalities aren\u2019t transparent about payments, the paper wrote. Some 20 external hires were paid more than the equivalent of the annual minister\u2019s salary of \u20ac179,000, according to AD\u2019s research.
