aVBrexit became a whole lot trickier for Theresa May when she lost her majority in June's snap election | Facundo Arrizabalaga/EPA Brexit Files Insight Tory shuffle to help push through Brexit law Theresa May accused of trying to \u2018rig parliament\u2019 by seeking a majority on important committees.\u000a\u000aLosing her majority in June\u2019s snap election made Brexit a whole lot trickier for Theresa May \u2014 but the government has a plan to help smooth its parliamentary progress.\u000a\u000aWithout a phalanx of Tory MPs cheerleading the plethora of legislation needed to ease Britain\u2019s EU exit through all stages of the process, the government risks tricky blockages.\u000a\u000aThe solution: To slip in a motion to be voted on late on Tuesday night, which will give the government a majority in standing committees \u2014 where clause-by-clause legislative heavy lifting takes place and parliamentary mischief can be made.\u000a\u000aLabour leader Jeremy Corbyn was quick out of the blocks, accusing ministers of an \u201cunprecedented attempt to rig parliament.\u201d\u000a\u000aMay, he claimed, has \u201cno majority and no mandate\u201d yet will stack committees with Tory MPs.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe government has to have a legitimate chance of getting its business through\u201d \u2014 Charles Walker\u000a\u000aBut Charles Walker, a Tory MP and chair of the influential procedure committee, which scrutinizes the way the House of Commons conducts its business, is less outraged by the move.\u000a\u000aWhile he expects \u201clively debate\u201d he thinks it is a \u201creasonable proposition.\u201d The logic is that, through its deal with the Democratic Unionist Party, the government has a working majority in the Commons, so it should also have a majority in the parliamentary committees that scrutinize legislation. Under the current rules, the DUP group is too small to qualify for committee seats, meaning that the government falls short.\u000a\u000aWalker told POLITICO that without the motion, \u201cyou could potentially see the legislative process grind to a halt.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThe government has to have a legitimate chance of getting its business through,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aBut he pointed out that there is a difference between commanding that majority and having that majority. \u201cIf you can\u2019t win the argument then you lose the vote. But the presumption should be that it starts from the position of having the ability to get its legislation through because it has a majority,\u201d he said, believing the majority of Tory MPs will be persuaded of that logic.\u000a\u000aThere are few signs of rebellion on the Tory and DUP side thus far, so the new rules are likely to be passed (probably).\u000a\u000aNonetheless, the government is holding its breath.\u000a\u000aOne senior Labour MP branded it \u201cthe biggest vote of this parliament.\u201d And Tory MPs have been told it is an unmissable vote.\u000a\u000aLook out for a Tuesday night parliamentary nail-biter.\u000a\u000aThis insight is from POLITICO\u2018s Brexit Files newsletter, a daily afternoon digest of the best coverage and analysis of Britain\u2019s decision to leave the EU. Read today\u2019s edition or subscribe here.
p122
aVFrench President Emmanuel Macron delivers a speech in Athens, Greece | Aris Messinis/AFP via Getty Images Macron urges \u2018maximum ambition\u2019 on eurozone budget, finance minister French president praises Greece for reforming to stay in the single currency area.\u000a\u000aPARIS \u2014 French President Emmanuel Macron on Thursday urged eurozone members to move with \u201cmaximum ambition\u201d toward adopting a common budget and finance minister, in defiance of Germany\u2019s position.\u000a\u000aSpeaking in Greece alongside President Prokopios Pavlopoulos, Macron heaped praise on his hosts for their efforts to carry out reforms and stay in the eurozone despite a crippling debt load and stringent savings goals.\u000a\u000aTo prevent future existential crises in the EU, the French president called for deeper integration between eurozone states, including a \u201creal eurozone budget [and a] a permanent finance minister who leads this executive.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThis is a democratic responsibility on the eurozone level, and as such it requires maximum ambition,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aMacron, who pushed for an overhaul of Europe\u2019s posted workers directive during a tour of Central and Eastern Europe last month, is casting himself as a European leader who can bring eurozone states closer together at a time when Britain is negotiating its way out of the bloc.\u000a\u000aSo far his proposals to create a eurozone parliament, common budget and finance minister have met with only muted approval in Germany. Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble endorsed the notion of a parliament and increasing the powers of the European Stability Mechanism (ESM) to bail out struggling countries.\u000a\u000aBut while Macron agreed with the need for a stronger ESM, and said the International Monetary Fund should not intervene in European affairs, he said the ESM was no replacement for a eurozone budget.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe European Stability Mechanism has a crisis management function, and we must activate it, and indeed we must move toward a European Monetary Fund, but this is in no way a budget,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s a mechanism for crisis management to allow different parties to recover from a crisis like the one that you had to go through.\u201d
