aVDamien Green , first secretary of state leaves 10 Downing Street on June 11, 2017 in London, England | Chris J Ratcliffe/Getty Images May\u2019s deputy: European Parliament doesn\u2019t set Brexit talks deadline British first secretary of state says \u2018UK need to continue to make the progress.\u2019\u000a\u000aBritish First Secretary of State Damian Green rejected remarks by European Parliament President Antonio Tajani that the U.K. would have to wait until nearly Christmas to start discussing its future relationship with the EU.\u000a\u000aTajani told POLITICO in an interview published Thursday that he would formally propose to senior MEPs on Thursday the postponing until December of the European Council\u2019s assessment of whether there has been \u201csufficient progress\u201d in the first phase of Brexit negotiations. The decision is currently expected in October.\u000a\u000aGreen told BBC Radio 4 Thursday morning that this deadline \u201cis not set by the European Parliament.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cWe need our own legislative house in order. We need to continue to make the progress that we need to make,\u201d Green said as MPs begin considering the general principles of the EU Withdrawal Bill on Thursday.\u000a\u000aGreen also commented on remarks by former European Council President Herman Van Rompuy, who said Thursday there is a \u201czero percent\u201d chance that enough progress will be made on exit issues by October to move on with Brexit talks.\u000a\u000aGreen said that was \u201ctoo pessimistic.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThese are complex negotiations, and there are several rounds to go,\u201d Green said. \u201cWe want to increase the pace, but there have been some significant agreements made already. Talks will be tough \u2014 let\u2019s see what happens between now and October.\u201d\u000a\u000aGreen further dismissed a Daily Telegraph report published Thursday that claimed he had distanced himself from leaked immigration policies to curb migration, for low-skilled workers in particular.\u000a\u000a\u201cThat report is nonsense, I have never seen what is leaked,\u201d he said, adding that he will only comment on government policies when they come out in \u201ca few weeks\u2019 time.\u201d\u000a\u000aGreen did say the government will need to propose changes to the current immigration system, because that will disappear when the U.K. leaves the EU.\u000a\u000aHe said the U.K. needs to make sure it attracts \u201cpeople that bring benefits to the country,\u201d and immigration numbers needed to be \u201ccontrolled and lowered.\u201d
