aVEmmanuel Macron at the Elysée palace | Alain Jocard/AFP via Getty Images Macron heads to Greece with big ideas but few specifics French president will give speech at site of early Athenian democracy.\u000a\u000aPARIS \u2014 Emmanuel Macron flies to Athens Thursday for a state visit with messages he hopes will reach a wider audience than the Greek politicians he wants to encourage on their bumpy road to economic reforms.\u000a\u000aThe French president will, in line with the policy of his predecessor François Hollande, reiterate his support for the Greek government\u2019s effort to clinch a deal with its eurozone partners to restructure the country\u2019s massive public debt. But he will also use an open-air speech on the Pnyx \u2014 the hill where citizens of ancient Athens used to hold their meetings \u2014 to restate his vision for the future of the EU, and the need for a more integrated monetary union.\u000a\u000aMacron\u2019s aides were keen this week to underline the symbolic nature of the French president\u2019s visit and speech in one of the cradles of democracy. But the same aides also implicitly acknowledged that Macron would be long on ideas and short on specifics \u2014 because most of the plans he has for Europe haven\u2019t yet been seriously discussed with his other European partners, most notably Germany, where a general election is just weeks away.\u000a\u000aBriefing reporters ahead of the trip, one presidential adviser seemed to take some pride in noting that Greek Prime Minister Alexis Tsipras will be the 12th EU leader Macron has met in the space of two weeks. The two-day formal visit will also be one of the French president\u2019s longest trips since he took office, following a series of quick hops in Europe since he came back from holiday on August 28.\u000a\u000aMacron\u2019s visit and speeches, however, will not only be aimed at other European leaders and citizens. On the domestic front, he is implementing the first phase of his reform agenda with an overhaul of labor laws, and is currently the most unpopular French president of modern times at this stage of the presidency. He wants to hammer home that his focus on a new French push for European integration is not an exercise in gratuitous self-aggrandizement, but a way to bring more prosperity at home down the road.\u000a\u000aMacron is traveling to Greece with Finance Minister Bruno Le Maire and some 40 CEOs of French companies, large and small, in a show of force designed to promote French exports and investment. \u201cWhen you look at [Greece\u2019s] growth numbers, investment picking up, unemployment still sky-high but shrinking, you clearly see the need to support Greece in this more positive moment,\u201d a presidential aide said.\u000a\u000aMacron will reiterate his view that Athens will deserve some form of debt restructuring once it has completed its current bailout program in a year\u2019s time. But he will not do anything that would break the so far united front of Greece\u2019s public creditors on the matter, the aide added.\u000a\u000aThe same will be true of eurozone reforms, where Macron isn\u2019t expected to go much further than his often-stated ideas on the creation of a eurozone budget supervised by a eurozone finance minister, and the need for \u201cmore democracy\u201d in decision-making around the monetary union.\u000a\u000aHe will stick to broad strokes because none of what he has in mind \u2014 much of it remaining fuzzy \u2014 has seriously been discussed with the German government. Only once a new government takes office in Berlin after the September 24 election will Macron push the issue.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe can\u2019t say that we need a more collective, democratic process and at the same time announce that a full and complete plan will be announced in Athens,\u201d the Macron aide said.
