aVBritish Prime Minister Theresa May welcomes European Parliament President Antonio Tajani in London | Daniel Leal-Olivas/AFP via Getty Images Theresa May to meet select group at European Parliament British prime minister turned down an invitation to address all MEPs.\u000a\u000aLONDON \u2014 Theresa May has agreed to address an exclusive gathering of European Parliament leaders.\u000a\u000aThe prime minister, who turned down an invitation to address all MEPs in a plenary session, informed European Parliament President Antonio Tajani she would be happy to address the Conference of Presidents. A date will now be arranged between No. 10 Downing Street and Tajani\u2019s team, a government official said.\u000a\u000aThe Conference of Presidents is chaired by Tajani and attended by the leaders of all the political groupings.\u000a\u000aThe prime minister said in June that she had been in \u201cdiscussions\u201d with Tajani about the possibility of becoming the first U.K. prime minister to address the European Parliament since Gordon Brown in 2009.\u000a\u000aHowever, a Downing Street official told POLITICO earlier this week there were \u201cno plans\u201d to address the Parliament.\u000a\u000aResponding, the Parliament\u2019s Brexit coordinator, former Belgian Prime Minister Guy Verhofstadt, said May had \u201cso far refused our invitations\u201d and urged her not to underestimate the importance of the Parliament.\u000a\u000a\u201cI fear the U.K. government and others are taking it for granted that MEPs will fall into line and agree any withdrawal agreement, but this would be a mistake,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aAn EU official said: \u201cTajani told political leaders a couple of hours ago that May has accepted an invite \u2014 but it will be a closed session just with a few of them.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Conference of Presidents, which meets twice a month, met Thursday and was given a presentation by Verhofstadt.\u000a\u000aA \u201cclear majority\u201d of leaders agreed the assessment on whether \u201csufficient progress\u201d on the first phase of Brexit negotiations was unlikely to be met by October, according to a press statement.\u000a\u000aThe Conference of Presidents decided the Parliament would adopt a resolution in October focusing on the rights of EU citizens in the U.K. and U.K. citizens in the EU post Brexit, and setting out its priorities on the Irish and Northern Irish border and assessing the financial situation.
