aVHolding skeptical views on oil and gas would seem to be electoral suicide in Norway, a country that became rich thanks to fossil fuel exports.\u000a\u000aBut two such parties look set to take seats in the September 11 vote, and potentially play a key role in the coalition building that usually follows Norwegian elections.\u000a\u000aLow oil prices, growing concerns over climate change and the rise of environmental parties have for the first time sparked a debate about whether Norway \u2014 one of the EU\u2019s leading gas suppliers \u2014 should be so reliant on one industry.\u000a\u000aThe Green Party wants a halt to oil and gas exploration and to phase out existing fields within 15 years. It took one seat in the 169-member Storting in 2013 with 2.8 percent of the vote, but a new poll conducted for state broadcaster NRK has the party with 4.2 percent support \u2014 enough to give it seven seats.\u000a\u000aThe Socialist Left, which currently holds seven seats, wants a ban on new permits for oil and gas drilling. The poll gives it 6.1 percent of the vote share, enough for 11 seats.\u000a\u000a\u201cFor the first time in Norwegian history, the future of the industry is under focus when people go to vote,\u201d said 22-year-old Anna Kvam, a first-time candidate from the Greens.\u000a\u000aLabor, the leading center-left party, is running at 24.4 percent in opinion polls. That would give it 46 seats, far short of the 85 needed for a majority. Labor says it won\u2019t work with the Greens, but most calculations of post-election coalition-building include at least one of the two oil and gas-skeptical parties.\u000a\u000aIn the 2013 election, Labor came first with 55 seats, but was unable to form a ruling coalition. That allowed the Conservative Party under the leadership of Prime Minister Erna Solberg to form a government together with the right-wing Progress Party and support from the smaller Christian Democrats and Liberals. The Conservatives have 25.7 percent in polls \u2014 and any coalition built by them is unlikely to include left-leaning environmentalists.\u000a\u000aIn the 2013 round of horse-trading, drilling in environmentally sensitive areas was an issue, but the future of oil and gas wasn\u2019t \u2014 especially because both the Conservatives and Labor support the sector and aren\u2019t keen to upend an industry that has made Norway one of the wealthiest countries on the planet.\u000a\u000aA lot has changed since then.\u000a\u000aNorway goes green\u000a\u000aThe Paris climate summit helped solidify views as to the seriousness of climate change \u2014 where Norway joined with the EU in pushing for an agreement to keep temperature rises to no more than 2 degrees Celsius. The country is a world leader in the adoption of electric cars, thanks in part to generous subsidies that are possible because of the money generated by selling oil and gas.\u000a\u000aRecent oil price turbulence also underlined the risk of being too tied to a single revenue stream.\u000a\u000a\u201cUntil the last few years it was almost impossible to talk about the implications of the oil industry and climate change in the same sentence,\u201d said Truls Gulowsen, head of Greenpeace in Norway. \u201cSomething is really happening.\u201d\u000a\u000aGulowsen said the fall in oil prices made the shift happen: The government reported a more than 40 percent drop in revenues from the sector in 2016 compared to 2015.\u000a\u000aAbout 50,000 people in the industry lost their jobs when crude prices collapsed in 2014 \u2014 a fifth of the sector\u2019s workforce at the time.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe tone in the debate has changed,\u201d said Labor MP Per Rune Henriksen, who was also state secretary for energy between 2010 and 2013. \u201cNow we are talking more about the economic risks in the oil and gas industry.\u201d\u000a\u000aKarl Eirik Schjøtt-Pedersen, director general at the Norwegian oil and gas association as well as a former minister and Labor MP, agreed the topic is higher on the agenda, and said that\u2019s because of the \u201cvery loud voices from the Greens.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cIt\u2019s a small minority advocating for changes,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aA recent survey from the Norwegian oil and gas association showed that 70 percent of Norwegians believe it is important to maintain the country\u2019s oil and gas industry \u2014 with young people more skeptical of the industry than older Norwegians. Another survey by the Dagbladet newspaper showed that 44 percent of Norwegians are willing to let some oil reserves remain in the ground to save the climate, while 42 percent disagree.\u000a\u000aThe fight over oil and gas is most acute in Norway\u2019s Arctic Lofoten and Vesterålen islands. The region is home to the world\u2019s largest cold-water coral reef and the source of most of Norway\u2019s fish supply \u2014 but it is also estimated to hold billions of barrels of crude.\u000a\u000aIndustry has been keen to drill there for years, but the current government was forced to keep the region off limits as part of a coalition deal after the last election. The government tried to reverse that ban last year, but was forced to retreat after a backlash from environmentalists and the fishing industry.\u000a\u000aA recent poll showed that 58 percent of respondents want to leave the Lofoten and Vesterålen free from oil drilling, while 27 percent want to recover the resources.\u000a\u000aDrill baby, drill\u000a\u000a\u201cThe potential is big for employment and for bringing additional income to the national treasury,\u201d said Elnar Remi Holmen, Norway\u2019s secretary of state for petroleum and energy from the Progress Party.\u000a\u000aProgress has been the most avid supporter of drilling in Lofoten and Vesterålen, while the Greens, the Socialist Left and the agrarian Center Party want to leave it oil-free.\u000a\u000aThe main parties are pro-exploration, but even they have had to soften their approach \u2014 a sign of the shifting debate.\u000a\u000aThe Conservatives pledged a thorough assessment to understand how drilling may affect tourism and the fisheries sector. Labor wants to partly open up the region to drilling, also following an initial assessment, but promised to avoid the most sensitive areas close to Lofoten\u2019s shores.\u000a\u000aKvam said she hopes opposition from \u201cthe big green block in the parliament\u201d will leave the area untouched.\u000a\u000aBut the industry is hopeful that the rise of environmental parties won\u2019t derail the country\u2019s traditional reliance on oil and gas.\u000a\u000aRegardless of which of the two big parties form the government in September, Schjøtt-Pedersen said that \u201cneither the Conservative Party nor the Labor Party will accept any essential changes to the country\u2019s oil and gas policy even if other parties put pressure.\u201d\u000a\u000aHenriksen, the Labor MP, said: \u201cAs long as there is a demand for oil and gas on the market, somebody has to produce it \u2026 Why should we keep our hands clean and let Saudi Arabia, Nigeria or the U.S. take this market?\u201d\u000a\u000aThis article has been updated with newer polling data.
