aVPARIS \u2014 Forget Emmanuel Macron, the \u201cJupiter-like\u201d president who spoke only in grand symbolic gestures.\u000a\u000aFrance\u2019s new leader is morphing into the explainer-in-chief.\u000a\u000aWith approval scores crashing, his predecessor, François Hollande, feeling bold enough to criticize him in public, and hard-left opponents scrapping for a fight, the 39-year-old president is being forced to reorient his communications strategy by 180 degrees.\u000a\u000aExit the quasi-North Korean grip on presidential messaging; the James Bond-like PR stunts; the hunt for leakers in ministerial offices; the ironclad rule against \u201coff-the-record\u201d talks; the ultra-rare presidential address.\u000a\u000aThe new Macron is ready to talk and to explain what he\u2019s trying to do \u2014 at least twice a month and preferably on the radio, according to accounts of the president\u2019s first off-the-record chat with journalists.\u000a\u000aHe is also pushing his ministers, MPs in his centrist La République en Marche movement and several newly hired comms staffers to back him up as often, and as loudly, as possible, on TV and radio.\u000a\u000aSince he took office, relations between the press and the new president have been strained, if not overtly hostile.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe president is not adapting to polls,\u201d said a presidential adviser. \u201cHe\u2019s adapting to a reform agenda that he\u2019s set for France, and that requires explanation before the French people to clarify its benefits and counteract the anxiety-inducing rhetoric of some critics.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhat for? To correct the course of a presidency that is veering off the rails amid missteps, overconfidence and rising opposition to his reform agenda.\u000a\u000aHollande\u2019s revenge\u000a\u000aIn practice, the shift means granting the public much more access to the president, via direct social media exchanges or more unscripted talks with journalists.\u000a\u000aLast week, for the first time since he took office, Macron had a long off-the-record \u2014 but comprehensively reported \u2014 chat with journalists from three publications (Le Monde, L\u2019Obs and regional Ouest-France) handpicked to join him on his Falcon aircraft from Salzburg to Bucharest.\u000a\u000aThe move raised eyebrows because Macron had frequently blasted his ex-boss and mentor, François Hollande, for similar chumminess with the fourth estate.\u000a\u000a\u201cI think the problem of recent presidencies has been too much closeness with journalists,\u201d the then candidate Macron said in April. \u201cAnd I think that, especially when you\u2019re the president, you don\u2019t pal around with reporters.\u201d\u000a\u000aHollande, an obsessive off-the-record talker, waited until Macron\u2019s popularity score was in Donald Trump territory to get his revenge. \u201cIt\u2019s not a good idea to ask the French for more sacrifices than is necessary,\u201d he told journalists in southwestern France.\u000a\u000aMore remarkable still was what Macron had to say to the journalists on his plane \u2014 he would now address the public twice each month, probably on the radio.\u000a\u000aThat struck a balance between familiarity and remoteness, and had pleasing historical echoes with Charles de Gaulle\u2019s wartime addresses from London to Franklin Delano Roosevelt\u2019s fireside chats, Macron reportedly said.\u000a\u000aAnd the president will be giving more print interviews too. Stepping out from his relationship with the weekly JDD paper, he has given one to right-leaning magazine Le Point that is due out on Wednesday.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, the president test-drove his new freewheeling communications plan during his tour of Central Europe, veering off-message during a joint press conference with his Austrian counterpart in Salzburg to defend domestic reforms.\u000a\u000aOne thing that\u2019s unlikely to change though is Macron\u2019s attitude toward set-piece press conferences at the Elysée presidential palace \u2014 a longstanding ritual he has shunned. He still finds them too unmanageable to be of any benefit, he is cited as having said.\u000a\u000aWar on leakers\u000a\u000aSince he took office, relations between the press and the new president have been strained, if not overtly hostile.\u000a\u000aWeeks after he entered office, his team cherry-picked journalists for his first trip abroad, prompting multiple media groups to denounce the practice in an open letter.\u000a\u000aWhen Richard Ferrand, a close ally to the president, was investigated on charges of nepotism, the government spokesman, Christophe Castaner, castigated journalists for trying to \u201cbehave like judges\u201d when they pressed him about ethics in public office \u2014 a key theme of Macron\u2019s campaign.\u000a\u000aThe question now is whether Macron\u2019s new presidential style will be more open, or just have the appearance of being so.\u000a\u000a(Ferrand is now head of the République En Marche group, but missed out on a more important ministerial role.)\u000a\u000aAnd staff in ministerial cabinets heard in no uncertain terms that the response to leaks would be legal action.\u000a\u000aTo dissuade potential leakers, the labor ministry in June filed a legal complaint \u2014 later withdrawn \u2014 against the person who leaked a working paper on its labor reform to center-left daily newspaper Libération.\u000a\u000aBeyond specific conflicts, journalists griped about a communications strategy that was overtly top-down, relentlessly agenda-driven and closed off to back-and-forth exchanges.\u000a\u000aThe president\u2019s office held frequent, exhaustive briefings but flatly refused to address questions on topics that were not on the agenda \u2014 there was no such thing as off-message.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, PR gatekeepers choked off access to advisers, or made the penalty for leaking information to the press so clear to them that the effect was essentially the same.\u000a\u000aThe question now is whether Macron\u2019s new presidential style will be more open, or just have the appearance of being so.
