aVThe EU's weapons export industry is the second largest in the world | Haidar Hamdani/AFP via Getty Images Parliament to discuss Saudi arms exports, secretive MEPs and Juncker\u2019s speech Plenary debates on North Korea and migration.\u000a\u000aMEPs on Friday set out their agenda for next week\u2019s plenary session in Strasbourg, the first since the summer break and at which the centerpiece will be Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker\u2019s State of the European Union.\u000a\u000aIt seems that MEPs have already forgotten about Juncker\u2019s pre-summer holiday outburst, when he described the assembly as \u201cridiculous, very ridiculous\u201d because of the low turn-out for a debate marking the end of the Maltese Council presidency featuring Prime Minister Joseph Muscat.\u000a\u000aWhen asked at the Parliament\u2019s \u201cpre-session briefing\u201d if any MEPs intended to show up for the State of the Union speech, only the Socialist group\u2019s spokeswoman, Utta Tuttlies, responded in the affirmative. However, it seems as if most MEPs will forgive and forget and show up to hear what Juncker has to say.\u000a\u000aDisability rights\u000a\u000aMEPs will next week vote on a new law known as the Accessibility Act, which will ensure goods and services are accessible for people with disabilities. Morten Løkkegaard, the Liberal MEP who led the discussions, has come under fire from the European Disability Forum (EDF) \u2014 and the Parliament\u2019s European United Left/Nordic Green Left group (GUE/NGL) \u2014 for putting business interests above disabled people.\u000a\u000aLucian Goleanu, a Liberal spokesman, dismissed claims that Løkkegaard had only listened to industry lobbyists, saying he felt the draft report was \u201cbalanced.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cI don\u2019t know why the [EDF] believes that this report is unbalanced or it is industry orientated,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aArms exports to Saudi Arabia\u000a\u000aMEPs are set to vote on a non-binding report on the EU\u2019s weapons export industry \u2014 the second largest in the world after the U.S.\u000a\u000aBodil Valero, a Swedish Green MEP who prepared the report, will ask MEPs to vote on a call to ban arms exports to Saudi Arabia over concerns that Riyadh is using the weapons in an ongoing conflict in Yemen.\u000a\u000aBoth the Socialists and the European People\u2019s Party on Friday declined to say if their MEPs would back the call for a ban. \u201cThe group is going to decide next week, so come back to us next week,\u201d said Lada Jurica, spokesperson for the EPP.\u000a\u000aLobby transparency\u000a\u000aMEPs will on Thursday vote on Green MEP Sven Giegold\u2019s report on transparency and ethics in the European institutions, which includes proposals for a longer cooling-off period for commissioners after they leave the Berlaymont.\u000a\u000aThe EPP and S&D have resisted calls to force MEPs to say which lobbyists they\u2019re meeting, despite some \u2014 such as the British Conservatives \u2014 having disclosed this information for years.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhen it comes to transparency, we will continue and have so far been in favor of transparency in the work of European parliamentarians,\u201d said the EPP\u2019s Jurica, before adding that MEPs need to \u201chave a certain liberty to exercise their mandate.\u201d
