aVThe Florida Republican is riding out the storm \u2014 which is expected to hit South Florida by Sunday morning \u2014 in his West Miami home, staying close to his 86-year-old mother, who lives in a nearby assisted living home. | AP Photo Rubio in Miami: Irma could 'overwhelm the system'\u000a\u000aMIAMI \u2014 From airports to banks to opioid addicts, Sen. Marco Rubio is warning that Hurricane Irma could "overwhelm the system" in Miami, as the nation's eighth-largest city \u2014 and leaders across the state \u2014 prepares for the storm amid a kind of creeping dread.\u000a\u000aThe Florida Republican is riding out the storm \u2014 which is expected to hit South Florida by Sunday morning \u2014 in his West Miami home, staying close to his 86-year-old mother, who lives in a nearby assisted living home.\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000a"You've got a lot of elderly people living in old structures and trailer parks who don't want to leave. You've got cruise ships dropping people off at the Port of Miami," Rubio told POLITICO by phone from his home. "You've got major airports in Miami, Fort Lauderdale, Palm Beach. I don't care if the towers open and the airlines are flying, you can't get anyone on the plane without TSA agents. And if those TSA agents live in Miami and were evacuated or harmed by the storm, it's going to be a while until you get them back to work."\u000a\u000aWhile downgraded from a Category 5 storm to a Category 4 storm Thursday, the storm's projected track has also shifted westward, and most models are now in agreement that the storm is likely to crash into South Florida sometime Sunday. The storm\u2019s latest path has it running up the center of the state, impacting nearly every region except the further western portions of the Panhandle.\u000a\u000aThe bottom line: A major hurricane as wide as the state is threatening landfall on either coast; the entire state is in the dreaded cone of uncertainty; the whole southern peninsula is under a hurricane warning and a warning for storm surge that could reach 10 feet. Hundreds of thousands of residents on the I-95 and I-75 corridors evacuated. There are traffic jams on every major northbound highway out of the southern peninsula. Store shelves from Naples to Miami and points north all the way to Jacksonville are picked clean of water, food, batteries, flashlights, plywood and screws. Fuel is sucked dry.\u000a\u000aGov. Rick Scott has taken the exceedingly rare step of closing pre-K-12, colleges and universities in all Florida\u2019s 67 counties through Monday. He also ordered the closure of state offices across the state. Scott has done a media barrage, offering updates and stressing the importance of people leaving the South Florida region \u2014 and of other Floridians being prepared to leave if needed.\u000a\u000a"Because of the nature of the storm and the trajectory, it has the capacity to overwhelm the system," Rubio said. "What if you're 86 years old and your Social Security check comes in on the 10th or the 15th. You don't have a bank. ... How do you get funds?"\u000a\u000a"All these [opiate addiction] sober homes in Palm Beach, run by shady operators, what do they do with all these patients living there and theoretically being treated? Do they just pick up and leave and now these people are on their own?" Rubio asked. "We've also got a substantial homeless population. ... You've got a lot of elderly people living in old structures and trailer parks who don't want to leave. You've got cruise ships dropping people off at the Port of Miami."\u000a\u000aRubio said small farming towns near the Everglades such as Belle Glade could also face flooding from Irma if it pushes a 10-foot storm surge up the River of Grass.\u000a\u000aAnd there's more: Aside from the short term shock of so many thousands leaving South Florida for Central and North Florida, Rubio said the state might have to prepare for a fresh influx of people from Puerto Rico, who have come to Florida in droves in recent years.\u000a\u000aPuerto Rico was "expecting a catastrophic entire-island wipeout" from Irma but dodged that fate, Rubio said. However, he added, the public utilities are decaying and some places could be without power for so long \u2014 some initial estimates projected as many as six months of blackouts \u2014 that more people will pick up and move to Florida.\u000a\u000a"In Florida, our utilities go down and you can drive trucks down from North Carolina," Rubio said. "In Puerto Rico, how do you get there? By sea."\u000a\u000aMatt Dixon in Tallahassee contributed to this report.
