aVGerman Foreign Minister Sigmar Gabriel and Chancellor Angela Merkel attend a weekly cabinet meeting in Berlin | Clemens Bilan/EPA Sigmar Gabriel surpasses Angela Merkel as most liked politician: poll SPD foreign minister is ranked top politician in Germany for the first time.\u000a\u000aA poll by Infratest Dimap for broadcaster ARD shows Germans are most pleased with the work of Foreign Minister Sigmar Gabriel \u2014 a first for the former Social Democrat (SPD) chairman.\u000a\u000aThe Deutschlandtrend survey published late Thursday showed 66 percent of respondents were \u201cpleased\u201d or \u201cvery pleased\u201d with Gabriel, placing him above Chancellor Angela Merkel, whose approval rating was 63 percent.\u000a\u000aBottom of the list with 10 percent approval was Alice Weidel, a lead candidate for the far-right Alternative for Germany (AfD) party.\u000a\u000a#Politikerzufriedenheit Merkel und Schulz legen zu, Gabriel zum ersten Mal auf Platz 1 /Mehr ARD #DeutschlandTREND https://t.co/fT8RwUl5h2 pic.twitter.com/mi2yPlsLJL \u2014 infratest dimap (@infratestdimap) September 8, 2017\u000a\u000aMerkel\u2019s key election rival and current SPD leader Martin Schulz stood in sixth place with 39 percent of respondents expressing approval of his work, an increase of 6 percentage points from an August poll.\u000a\u000aGabriel\u2019s resurgence in popularity comes as Schulz struggles to make gains on Merkel to oust her in the September 24 election.\u000a\u000aWhile Schulz hoped to win support during last Sunday\u2019s televised debate, the sole broadcast involving the two leading candidates, the Deutschlandtrend survey showed his party lost 2 percentage points compared with an August 31 survey.\u000a\u000aWhile the SPD fell to 21 percent support, Merkel\u2019s conservative CDU/CSU bloc held at 37 percent.\u000a\u000aWhen asked, hypothetically, who they would vote for if they could directly elect the chancellor, 54 percent of respondents named Merkel \u2014 an increase of 5 percentage points on the previous poll. Schulz remained steady at 26 percent.
