aVPARIS \u2014 If Emmanuel Macron was worried about his nosediving popularity, he ain\u2019t seen nothing yet.\u000a\u000aAs his government prepares to unveil a far-reaching overhaul of labor rules on Thursday, the far left and trade unions are preparing to fight back with nationwide street protests throughout September.\u000a\u000aThe looming showdown over workers\u2019 rights in a country where they are revered by much of the left is set to be the biggest test yet of Macron\u2019s authority and determination, at a time when his popularity is plummeting.\u000a\u000aThe big question is: Will Macron be able to resist the onslaught and fulfill his promise to make the French economy competitive again? Or will he follow generations of his predecessors who balked when the going got tough?\u000a\u000aWhile the exact contents of the overhaul are being kept a secret, a trade union boss who didn\u2019t wish to be named said they would deliver \u201cthe most profound overhaul\u201d of France\u2019s 3,492-page labor code \u201csince World War II.\u201d He added that most unions were waiting to see the published decrees before deciding how to react, and that the hardline CGT union risked being isolated in its complete opposition to the reforms.\u000a\u000aAsked Wednesday about the president\u2019s commitment to reform in the face of stiffening opposition, government spokesman Christopher Castaner said: \u201cAfter the final round of the presidential election, Emmanuel Macron told me \u2018We have won the right to take risks.'\u201d\u000a\u000aHe added: \u201cDo you think he is the type of person to change his approach based on polling? I don\u2019t think so.\u201d\u000a\u000aMacron will face stiffer headwinds than ever before. Failure could come in many forms, particularly if he bows to pressure and waters down his reforms.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe\u2019ve got our backs against the wall,\u201d said Pierre Gattaz, head of France\u2019s main employers\u2019 lobby, MEDEF. \u201cIt\u2019s extremely important that the government\u2019s hand not tremble \u2026 and that there not be 1,000 counter-parties, 1,000 restrictions, 1,000 exceptions.\u201d\u000a\u000aStreets of rage\u000a\u000aMacron has one major advantage when taking on the doubters: He can rely on firm support from the lower house of parliament, where his centrist La République en Marche party commands an absolute majority.\u000a\u000aThe labor code changes, to be presented by Prime Minister Édouard Philippe and Labor Minister Muriel Pénicaud on Thursday, do not require approval by parliament, though they will need to be signed off on by France\u2019s Constitutional Court.\u000a\u000aFrom a legislative standpoint, almost nothing stands in Macron\u2019s way. And poll scores will not change the fact that his MPs control parliament, no matter how low they go.\u000a\u000aYet the normally bullish president showed a rare flash of self-doubt while in Bucharest last week when he declared that France was \u201cunreformable,\u201d in comments that critics said betrayed misgivings about his chances of success. Macron, who made the unusually strong remarks when speaking to Romania\u2019s French community, added that the French \u201chated reform\u201d and the only way to change the country was to do so while leading the European Union into a new phase of integration.\u000a\u000aFrom the start of the labor reform process, government negotiators took pains to keep the talks secret, striking a deal with unions not to leak working documents. Government met with unions some 100 times, although they often held separate meetings with them to discuss the same topics. The five unions involved mostly toed the line, although the CGT said early on that it opposed the spirit of the changes, with chief Philippe Martinez adding in August that the reform was a \u201clie\u201d by the state.\u000a\u000aWhen a leaked document ended up in left-leaning daily Libération, the labor ministry launched legal action, later withdrawn, against the author of the leak (known merely as \u201cX\u201d in the lawsuit).\u000a\u000aMacron\u2019s government was keen to avoid labor talks overshadowing its broader legislative agenda, namely a law on ethics for lawmakers. It also wanted to avoid fueling opposition from the far-left, led by Jean-Luc Mélenchon, or even from far-right leader Marine Le Pen, both of whom now have seats in parliament. Mélenchon in particular has a chance to prove his political clout by attracting big crowds to protests, although he has opted not to join forces with unions.\u000a\u000aIf Macron and his team are circumspect, it\u2019s because they understand how explosive the topic of labor reform is. Few subjects are more contentious in France and street movements are a formidable force that crushes reforms and brings down governments.\u000a\u000aMacron may be France\u2019s youngest leader in more than a century, but he was an 18-year-old student when national strikes brought down the government of then-prime minister Alain Juppé, burying his attempt to reform the pension system. Macron was 29 when a national student uprising against a proposed \u201cfirst job\u201d contract cowed then-prime minister Dominique de Villepin. He was 37 and serving under François Hollande as economy minister when his boss burned through any remaining political capital he had in order to pass a labor reform, since derided as pointless, after weeks of protests.\u000a\u000a\u201cI view them with respect,\u201d said Castaner when asked about the upcoming protests. \u201cIt\u2019s our responsibility to explain the benefits of this reform.\u201d\u000a\u000aIf they fail to do so, negative opinions of Macron and his agenda will keep piling up, and more people will turn out to protest. Macron will not lose his job, and Prime Minister Philippe is unlikely to do so either. But they could lose their zeal to reform.\u000a\u000aDeath by a thousand cuts\u000a\u000aIn the short term, a greater fear among those who invest in France is that Macron will compromise the substance of his reforms in ways that will ultimately render them toothless.\u000a\u000aAccording to the trade union boss, the labor code changes will allow unions and companies to negotiate most working conditions at the company or factory level, as opposed to that work being done on a sector-by-sector level, as is currently the case.\u000a\u000aThat would bring French labor laws closer to current standards in Germany or Sweden, for example, while depriving hard-line unions of much of their national negotiating power.\u000a\u000aAnother expected big change is the creation of a set scale for severance pay after dismissal. Currently, there is no way to predict how much a dismissal will cost once it goes to arbitration. A fixed scale would make the process more predictable.\u000a\u000aOn both fronts, Macron\u2019s government could quietly give ground in ways that would drain the reform of its value. By accepting that some topics, such as the maximum length of the working week, would remain the subject of sectoral negotiations, they would undermine their plans to bring in greater flexibility. By scrapping the severance pay scale, they would sacrifice the predictability desired by investors.\u000a\u000aStarting on Thursday, Macron\u2019s government has a month during which it can revise its executive decrees before they are sent to the Constitutional Court for final approval. The intensity of the protests will likely determine the government\u2019s willingness to cede ground.\u000a\u000aOne point in Macron\u2019s favor: The front against him is divided, with Mélenchon\u2019s troops protesting on September 23, 11 days after the CGT trade union, and other unions so far undecided on whether to join in.
