aVPoliticians in Brussels are both the biggest cheerleaders and staunchest foes of constant connectivity.\u000a\u000aEU officials have repeatedly touted the benefits of high-speed mobile internet in a series of recent policy documents. But just a mile down the road from European Commission headquarters, the Brussels regional government has for years hampered the rollout of new mobile network technology amid health concerns about radiation exposure.\u000a\u000aWith the dawn of the Internet of Things, taking all kinds of gadgets and even cars online, telecoms players in Belgium\u2019s various levels of government are under pressure to sort out their differences.\u000a\u000a\u201cBrussels risks becoming a medieval island in a digital Europe,\u201d said Alexander De Croo, digital minister and vice prime minister in Belgium\u2019s federal government.\u000a\u000aA lack of connectivity already causes problems in both day-to-day life and for security services in responding to crises. What\u2019s more, EU officials have bet their political capital on the successful rollout of 5G, the next-generation mobile technology.\u000a\u000aBrussels\u2019 environmental norms for radiation are 50 times stricter than the standards set by an international commission under the World Health Organization.\u000a\u000aA decade ago, Brussels\u2019 local lawmakers instituted strict environmental limits on the mobile telecoms-related radiation levels across town. This angered telecoms executives, who lashed out at what they think is an outdated policy. Telecoms services delayed investing in stronger wireless mobile coverage and Brussels was late in adopting the current 4G technology.\u000a\u000aIn Europe\u2019s capital, seat of the EU institutions, there\u2019s little case for investing in more powerful technology, according to telecoms companies.\u000a\u000a\u201cToday, we estimate that [5G] won\u2019t be possible [in Brussels],\u201d said Coralie Miserque, a spokeswoman for Telenet, one of Belgium\u2019s two dominant telecoms operators. \u201cWe have to adapt our network \u2026 [but it\u2019s] already saturated.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe Commission\u2019s 5G action plan calls for early adoptions as soon as next year and large-scale market roll-out by 2020. New high-speed mobile internet networks are being tested across the world, and Europe wants to catch up with pioneering countries such as South Korea, China, and the U.S.\u000a\u000aJust last month, national telecoms ministers from across Europe agreed to \u201cposition Europe as the global lead market for 5G.\u201d\u000a\u000aWithout more bandwidth, the new technology can\u2019t be rolled out in Brussels. \u201cIf we want to be a digital capital, this is impossible,\u201d Miserque said.\u000a\u000aGetting online\u000a\u000aBrussels\u2019 environmental norms for radiation are 50 times stricter than the standards set by an international commission under the World Health Organization. Telecoms companies\u2019 own estimates say they are among the strictest in the world.\u000a\u000aThis leads to bad connections across town because the networks aren\u2019t allowed to broadcast sufficiently powerful signals to ensure a steady connection. For example, mobile internet is often cut when walking alongside the Commission\u2019s Berlaymont headquarters.\u000a\u000aIn past reports, the country\u2019s telecoms regulator has flagged that the Brussels\u2019 telecoms radiation limits force Belgian consumers to have worse internet connections at higher prices.\u000a\u000aOn March 22, 2016, when terrorists struck Brussels\u2019 airport and metro, killing 32 people and injuring hundreds, cell towers couldn\u2019t handle the traffic, leaving many unable to call or text. National politicians blamed Brussels\u2019 radiation standards for the weak wireless coverage.\u000a\u000aDuring the attacks, one operator, Base, ignored the radiation limits when its network overheated. It later nudged policymakers to address the issue of capacity in times of crisis, but the Brussels government pushed back when requests were made to relax the limits more widely.\u000a\u000aA year-and-a-half later, telecoms operators and security services struck a political deal to breach radiation limits in times of crisis. They remain the same the rest of the time.\u000a\u000aPolitical decision\u000a\u000aSome suggest that Brussels\u2019 limits are more a result of politics than health concerns.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe right norm \u2014 that\u2019s not something that\u2019s clear-cut. It\u2019s a political decision,\u201d said Guy Vandenbosch, a professor in telecoms technologies at the Catholic University Leuven.\u000a\u000aSo far, the current ruling coalition of Socialist, Liberal and centrist parties hasn\u2019t tabled any legislation to amend the rules.\u000a\u000aThe limits date back to laws introduced in 2007 and 2009, the legacy of two consecutive coalition governments that included Green parties that pushed heavily for strict environmental controls.\u000a\u000aThey have been challenged before Belgium\u2019s Constitutional Court by none other than the country\u2019s federal government, among other legal institutions, as well as by telecoms operators. But this has failed to bring down the laws.\u000a\u000aSo far, the current ruling coalition of Socialist, Liberal and centrist parties hasn\u2019t tabled any legislation to amend the rules. Brussels Environment Minister Céline Fremault did not respond to POLITICO\u2019s questions in time for publication.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, Vandenbosch noted that the experts\u2019 views on the health risks of mobile-network radiation levels are nuanced.\u000a\u000a\u201cThere have been plenty of studies on the effects of [telecoms] radiation, but no immediate effects and almost no mid-term effects have been found,\u201d he said. The long-term effects are still unknown.\u000a\u000aIn practice, this means the Brussels government opted for limits that scientists dub are \u201cas low as technically achievable,\u201d Vandenbosch said.\u000a\u000a\u201cLawmakers, without fully realizing it, followed this principle,\u201d said Vandenbosch, adding that, as far as health is concerned, \u201cthat\u2019s not such a bad thing.\u201d
