aVLONDON \u2014 Westminster\u2019s warren of corridors, plethora of pubs and cast of ambitious characters makes it the perfect stage for political plotting.\u000a\u000aBut it is also the backdrop to many a romantic liaison, where you might be surprised to discover that your lunch partner is more than familiar with the subject of your conversation.\u000a\u000aHere is POLITICO\u2019s guide to the Westminster power couples you need to know.\u000a\u000aTrue blue veterans\u000a\u000aBernard and Anne Jenkin\u000a\u000aThis pair met at the 1984 Conservative Party conference in Brighton \u2014 the year an IRA bomb was planted in an attempt assassinate then Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.\u000a\u000aBernard Jenkin\u2019s father, who was then in the Cabinet and had been staying in the Grand Hotel where the bomb went off, met his future daughter-in-law for the first time when the young romantics eventually found him in a nearby hotel for the evacuated.\u000a\u000aBernard Jenkin, an MP since 1992, is chairperson of the public administration and constitutional affairs committee and on the pro-Brexit European Research Group steering committee. Anne Jenkin, who was given a seat in the House of Lords in 2011, leads the party\u2019s Women2Win offshoot, which she set up with Prime Minister Theresa May to boost the number of female Tory MPs in 2005.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: Walks on an Essex beach, seclusion away from public life, concerts, jobs about the house and entertaining are the couple\u2019s shared interests.\u000a\u000aGood stock: The pair both come from strong political pedigree. As well as Bernard Jenkin\u2019s Cabinet minister father, three of Anne Jenkin\u2019s grandparents were in the House of Lords, one was the only Tory woman elected as an MP in 1945. The Jenkins have two grown-up boys.\u000a\u000aGreat to be with @bernardjenkin and @GilesWatling in #Harwich to support 'This is Tendring' Britannia Ball for #RNLI pic.twitter.com/8NMo2F1etU \u2014 Anne Jenkin (@Baronessjenkin) June 30, 2017\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aResearcher romance\u000a\u000aNatalie Evans and James Wild\u000a\u000aLeader of the House of Lords Natalie Evans \u2014 the youngest member of May\u2019s Cabinet \u2014 does not work far from her Ministry of Defense special adviser husband, James Wild.\u000a\u000aLove blossomed in the economics section of the Conservative Research Department, when William Hague was leader of the opposition. Wild covered the Department of Trade and Industry, as it was then, and Evans the Treasury. Former Prime Minister David Cameron elevated Evans to the House of Lords after she led the New Schools Network charity, a job subsequently held by Theresa May\u2019s former chief of staff Nick Timothy. Wild now advises U.K. Defense Secretary Michael Fallon.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: Keen cricketers, Wild and Evans always get to England test matches and both played in the recent Lords and Commons team against the Lashings Cricket Club (made up of former test cricketers). They also hold Norwich City Football Club season tickets in Norfolk, where Wild has family and stood unsuccessfully for North Norfolk in the snap election.\u000a\u000aFeline friend: Hetty, their cat, usually wakes the couple up before their early morning alarm clock.\u000a\u000aBrexit baby\u000a\u000aAndrea Jenkyns and Jack Lopresti\u000a\u000aAndrea Jenkyns first caught public attention when she defeated former Labour Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls in his Morley and Outwood seat by a margin of just 422 votes in the 2015 general election. Once in Westminster, she met Jack Lopresti, the MP for Filton and Bradley Stoke, and the couple began dating later that year. The Sun carried pictures of the couple in matching elf jumpers at a staff party and reported that Lopresti was still married.\u000a\u000aBrexit baby: Their baby Clifford George was born on the day Article 50 was triggered \u2014 and his arrival was announced in the House of Commons.\u000a\u000aThrilled to announce that at 42, I am having a baby with my partner Jack. https://t.co/UMSrJLrwvb pic.twitter.com/AJPH4AY7FH \u2014 Andrea Jenkyns MP (@andreajenkyns) November 16, 2016\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWedded watchdogs\u000a\u000aRobert Chote and Sharon White\u000a\u000aRobert Chote and Sharon White each have a powerful watchdog to oversee. Chote marks the U.K. Treasury\u2019s homework at the Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR), while White keeps Britain\u2019s telecoms, postal services and broadcast media in check at regulator Ofcom.\u000a\u000aWhite arrived at Ofcom via the British Embassy in Washington (where the couple married) and then Tony Blair\u2019s Downing Street. Chote began his career as a journalist at the Independent and Financial Times newspapers and headed the Institute for Fiscal Studies think tank before taking the helm at the OBR.\u000a\u000aBrainiacs: The pair both studied economics at Cambridge, but met through a mutual friend two years after they left university.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: Talk is usually domestic practicalities at their home in Tufnell Park in north London. Most non-work time is spent ferrying their two children around, though they manage to get to the theater and concerts when they can.\u000a\u000aMinisterial matrimony\u000a\u000aMark Lancaster and Caroline Dinenage\u000a\u000aNot many newlyweds get personal congratulations in the House of Commons, but former Prime Minister David Cameron did just that when this pair of Tory MPs married in February 2014.\u000a\u000aBoth are part of the current government, Lancaster as a minister at the Ministry of Defense and Dinenage at the Department for Work and Pensions.\u000a\u000aTime apart: Constituency time is long-distance. They represent places that are 120 miles apart \u2014 Dinenage representing the south coast town of Gosport, while Lancaster is the MP for Milton Keynes North.\u000a\u000aPets and kids: The pair have three children between them from previous relationships, and three fish.\u000a\u000aLobby love\u000a\u000aPatrick Wintour and Rachel Sylvester\u000a\u000aWintour \u2014 former Guardian political editor and now the paper\u2019s diplomatic editor \u2014 met Sylvester \u2014 the Times columnist whose interview with Andrea Leadsom stalled the Brexiteer\u2019s leadership bid in the summer of 2016 \u2014 when they were both working for Sunday papers in the lobby.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: Sylvester told POLITICO they do talk about politics a bit at home because they both find it interesting. \u201cIt\u2019s not really talking shop, it\u2019s just talking about the world,\u201d she said.\u000a\u000aChildren: The pair have four children between them, aged 22, 20, 13 and 10 (the older two are Sylvester\u2019s step-children), and two cats. They are currently engaged in a guerrilla war with foxes that are destroying their garden.\u000a\u000aSunday rivals\u000a\u000aJane Merrick and Toby Helm\u000a\u000aUntil Merrick went freelance two years ago, this pair were Sunday political editor rivals \u2014 Merrick at the Independent on Sunday and Helm at the Observer. They met in the lobby when Merrick was working at the Daily Mail and Helm was at the Telegraph.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: \u201cWe still talk about politics all the time,\u201d Merrick told POLITICO.\u000a\u000aIn the blood: Their seven-year-old daughter delighted in breaking the news to her classmates that the prime minister had just resigned after watching David Cameron\u2019s final speech from Downing Street over breakfast the day after the Brexit vote.\u000a\u000aLabour love\u000a\u000aJack Dromey and Harriet Harman\u000a\u000aEquality champion Harriet Harman describes in her autobiography, \u201cA Woman\u2019s Work,\u201d how she and Shadow Business Minister Dromey worked together in the mid-1970s in a back room at the Brent Law Centre in a space so small their two desks had to be pushed together. Harman was first elected in 1982 and went on to serve as solicitor general, minister for women and leader of the House of Commons, as well as two stints as leader of the opposition. Dromey, a trade unionist, has been MP for Birmingham Erdington since 2010.\u000a\u000aAhead of the times: The pair cohabited without being married in the days when it was thoroughly disapproved of. Harman wrote of her relationship: \u201cMy job and my partner was very different from what my parents hoped for me. I was working at a law center rather than in a respectable solicitors\u2019 practice. And Jack could not have been further from the professional middle-class husband they had envisaged.\u201d\u000a\u000aDowning Street devotion\u000a\u000aLizzie Loudon and Will Tanner\u000a\u000aLizzie Loudon, the prime minister\u2019s former press secretary, and Will Tanner, her former deputy head of policy, met during Theresa May\u2019s short-lived leadership campaign. They really got to know each other after May became prime minister while working at No. 10. Both have left Downing Street since the general election. Loudon is now a partner at political advisory group Hanbury Strategy while Tanner is chief policy adviser at Portland Communications.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: Loudon says they don\u2019t really talk about work at home, but share a common interest \u2014 and lots of friends \u2014 in politics so would naturally discuss what\u2019s going on in Westminster. The have just returned from a holiday in Sicily.\u000a\u000aNorthern Irish nuptials\u000a\u000aNigel and Diane Dodds\u000a\u000aLeader of the DUP in the House of Commons Nigel Dodds and MEP Diane Dodds met when Nigel was studying at the Institute of Professional Legal Studies at Queen\u2019s University in Belfast where Diane was a history undergraduate, according to an interview in the Belfast Telegraph.\u000a\u000aNot just a big name in Northern Ireland, Nigel Dodds is now a significant figure in the rest of the U.K. after his party did a deal with the Conservatives to keep Theresa May in power after she failed to secure a majority in the June snap election.\u000a\u000aChildren: The pair had three children, but their middle son, Andrew, sadly died. \u201cOur middle boy, Andrew, passed away aged eight in 1998. We believe strongly in God\u2019s providence \u2014 doors open and close along life\u2019s journey, which guide us in the direction God would have us go,\u201d Nigel Dodds told the Belfast Telegraph.\u000a\u000aWorlds collide\u000a\u000aPeter Dominiczak and Lottie Dexter\u000a\u000aDominiczak and Dexter met for a working lunch at Inn the Park in Regent\u2019s Park when he was the Daily Telegraph\u2019s political editor and she was special adviser to the then Business and Energy Minister Matt Hancock. Times have changed for the pair.\u000a\u000aDominiczak has left journalism and now works for Lynton Crosby\u2019s CTF Partners \u2014 the architect of election wins for former Prime Minister David Cameron, Boris Johnson\u2019s victory in his first London mayoral race in 2008 and Theresa May\u2019s less successful snap election campaign.\u000a\u000aFirst born: Dexter, who has been on maternity leave after having the pair\u2019s first son, Hector, will return to work for First Secretary of State Damian Green, now de facto deputy prime minister, in the new year.\u000a\u000aPolitical editor and Cameron\u2019s media guru\u000a\u000aTim Shipman and Charlotte Todman\u000a\u000aSunday Times Political Editor and \u201cAll Out War\u201d author Tim Shipman is married to David Cameron\u2019s former head of media operations Charlotte Todman. Pre-Cameron, Todman was personal assistant to his predecessor, former Prime Minister Gordon Brown, and also worked in Ed Miliband\u2019s private office at the Cabinet Office. She was head of events for the official Remain campaign, Britain Stronger In Europe, and is now a communications and campaigns consultant.\u000a\u000a\u201cWhen I wrote a story [Todman] didn\u2019t like during the referendum I was made to sleep in the spare room for two nights,\u201d Shipman told POLITICO.\u000a\u000aNew York, New York: The pair met in a limousine in New York during the U.N. General Assembly in 2011, and again in the Red Lion pub five months later. They married in July 2015.\u000a\u000aAfter hours: The pair claim not to talk shop at home too much, and relax by seeing friends, watching TV box sets, going to comedy shows and the theater.\u000a\u000aHonorable mentions\u000a\u000aMatt Goshko, director of press at the U.S. Embassy, and Susannah Goshko, deputy director at the Department for Exiting the European Union.\u000a\u000aSpectator Political Editor James Forsyth and Allegra Stratton, former Newsnight political editor poached by ITV, are married.\u000a\u000aAssistant Editor of the Spectator Isabel Hardman and Labour MP John Woodcock are a notable Westminster item.\u000a\u000aLabour MP Stephen Kinnock is married to the former Danish prime minister, now CEO of Save the Children International Helle Thorning-Schmidt.\u000a\u000aExeter MP and former culture secretary Ben Bradshaw is married to BBC producer Neal Dalgleish.\u000a\u000aFormer Ed Miliband spokesperson James Stewart and Sky News Political Correspondent Tamara Cohen.\u000a\u000aMinister and member of the Johnson clan Jo Johnson and Guardian Social Affairs Editor Amelia Gentlemen are married.\u000a\u000aShadow Justice Minister Gloria De Piero is married to Labour deputy leader Tom Watson\u2019s director of communications, James Robinson.\u000a\u000aHome affairs committee chairperson Yvette Cooper and former Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls were the first ever married Cabinet minister couple.\u000a\u000aShadow Brexit Minister Jenny Chapman is married to shadow whip Nick Smith.\u000a\u000aBBC Westminster Hour presenter Carolyn Quinn and i newspaper Political Editor Nigel Morris are another example of lobby love.\u000a\u000aShadow Health Secretary Jonathan Ashworth is married to Labour Party Executive Director Emilie Oldknow.\u000a\u000aThe Liberal Democrats\u2019 deputy leader Jo Swinson is married to former Liberal Democrat MP Duncan Hames, who is believed to be the first MP to take a baby through a voting lobby.\u000a\u000aJim Waterson, Buzzfeed political editor, and Jess Brammar, deputy editor at BBC Newsnight, are an item.\u000a\u000aSamana Haq, who will shortly be head of news at the Ministry of Justice after eight years in the lobby as ITV News Westminster news editor, married Carl Dinnen, ITV political correspondent, earlier this year.\u000a\u000aFormer Press Secretary to the Prince of Wales Mark Bolland is married to Guy Black, who sits in the House of Lords as Baron Black of Brentwood and is also executive director of the Telegraph Media Group.\u000a\u000aAlan Beith, who sits in the House of Lords as Lord Beith, is married to former president of the Liberal Democrats and fellow peer Diana Maddock.\u000a\u000aBenedict Brogan, former deputy editor of the Telegraph, now director of group public affairs at Lloyds Banking Group, is married to the Department for Communities and Local Government Permanent Secretary Melanie Dawes.\u000a\u000aConservative MP John Penrose is married to Cheltenham Racecourse board member and non-executive director of the Bank of England, Diana \u201cDido\u201d Harding, who sits in the House of Lords as Lady Harding of Winscombe.\u000a\u000aLabour MP Jon Cruddas is married to long-serving Labour Party special adviser Anna Healy, who was made a life peer in 2010 and sits in the House of Lords as Baroness Healy of Primrose Hill.
