aVTerrorism tops list of Germans\u2019 biggest fears: survey New study reveals Germans biggest concerns, which include natural disasters and pollutants in food.\u000a\u000aGermans are most afraid of terrorism, followed by political extremism and tensions caused by immigration, according to a study published Thursday.\u000a\u000aThe survey found that people had worries across a range of topics, from politics to family, from the environment to health, but security was the biggest cause for concern.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe fear of terror attacks is in first place by a great distance,\u201d said Brigitte Römstedt, the head of R + V Infocenter, which carried out the study, Bild reported.\u000a\u000aThe European debt crisis also has Germans worried, with 58 percent afraid that it might have an impact on their taxes. Also in the top 10 list were pollutants in food, a fear of natural disasters, and excessive demands placed on the country by an increasing number of asylum seekers.\u000a\u000aJust over a third of respondents said having Donald Trump in the White House made them fear that Germany would lose an important international partner.\u000a\u000aR + V carried out the research in June and July.
