aVAlthough he leads the traditional party of the Norwegian working class, Jonas Gahr Støre has a patrician background and is an heir to considerable wealth | Alex Wong/Getty Images Norwegian party\u2019s pledge: Vote for us, we\u2019ll raise your taxes Opposition party accuses government of spending way too much, and only tax hikes can balance the books.\u000a\u000aOSLO \u2014 Norwegian Labor Party leader Jonas Gahr Støre reached out to voters with a brutally honest pledge \u2014 he\u2019s going to raise their taxes if elected prime minister next week.\u000a\u000aA year ago, Norway\u2019s general election on September 11 looked like a certain victory for Støre\u2019s Labor-led center-left bloc over Conservative Prime Minister Erna Solberg\u2019s center-right coalition government. Now they are neck-and-neck in the polls.\u000a\u000aSolberg\u2019s Conservative Party has attacked Labor\u2019s platform by suggesting the party will raise taxes by more than it says if it gets into power, or will be forced to do so by its leftist allies in a governing coalition. But the Norwegian left says there is no option but to raise taxes because of the way the Conservatives have been spending money and giving tax breaks to the rich.\u000a\u000a\u201cDo you know how much money they have spent? It\u2019s a piñata,\u201d said Bjørn Jacobsen, who is running for parliament for the Socialist Left Party (SV) in the county of Møre og Romsdal. His party is a likely junior coalition partner if Labor gets into power.\u000a\u000aJacobsen shares the widespread feeling in Norway that it will be a very close contest on Monday, though he expects the outcome to be a coalition of Labor, the rural Center Party and the Socialist Left.\u000a\u000aBernt Aardal, a political scientist at the University of Oslo, predicts it will be \u201cvery close, both in terms of the election result and what is going to happen with the government afterwards.\u201d The uncertainty stems partly from weak support for many smaller parties, some of which could fail to reach the 4 percent election threshold, and from shifts in strength between parties in opposing blocs.\u000a\u000aThough it\u2019s a safe bet that either Støre or Solberg will be prime minster, the daily Aftenposten recently listed 10 different possible government coalition constellations. A weak result for Labor could force Støre to rely heavily on the small Green and/or Red parties for support, which could make governing difficult and hand the tiny parties considerable power.\u000a\u000aWelfare costs money\u000a\u000aEgalitarian Norway already has steeply progressive income-tax rates, with a top marginal rate of 46.7 percent, and a total tax burden of around 45 percent, which is above the OECD average.\u000a\u000a\u201cTax is not so important as what we shall do with it \u2014 we want to have as low taxes as possible, but as high as necessary,\u201d Støre said in an interview on national broadcaster NRK, reconfirming his pledge to raise the total tax take by up to 15 billion Norwegian kroner ($1.93 billion).\u000a\u000aHe said Norway needs that money to invest in teachers, to deal with an aging population and to boost job training.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe kept our tax promise in 2005, 2009, 2013, and we will keep it in 2017,\u201d Støre said.\u000a\u000a\u201cI think it is honest to say that if we are going to do what we want to do, we have to raise taxes. I think it is an honest thing, and there is some dignity in it\u201d \u2014 Anders Tangen\u000a\u000aThough voters are showing signs of fatigue with Solberg\u2019s minority coalition of her Conservatives and the populist Progress Party, the disillusionment does not seem as rampant as when voters in 2013 ousted the previous Labor-led coalition, which had governed for eight years under Støre\u2019s predecessor, Jens Stoltenberg.\u000a\u000aStoltenberg\u2019s approach, when he won power in 2005 for a second time, had been to tell the people not to expect tax cuts; Støre has gone one better and chosen to campaign on a promise to raise taxes.\u000a\u000aFor the social democratic Labor Party, which is the biggest party with 55 seats in the 169-seat parliament, that means rolling back tax cuts granted by the Solberg government to high earners and the rich. But in a country where income differences are smaller than in many others, the planned tax increases would not affect only the super-rich, but also people earning a high, though not extravagant, annual income of more than 600,000 Norwegian kroner ($77,120).\u000a\u000aSo, it\u2019s a \u201csoak the rich\u201d strategy that would affect Norwegians who likely think of themselves as unmistakably middle-class \u2014 and unwilling to hand over more to the taxman.\u000a\u000aThe tabloid VG in July launched on its website a \u201cJonas Tax calculator\u201d (named after Støre), where readers can plug in their financial details to find out if or by how much Støre\u2019s tax-hike pledge will affect them.\u000a\u000aTruls Wickholm, a Labor lawmaker from Oslo who sits on the parliament\u2019s finance and economic committee, said the party felt \u201cthe need to be upfront with voters about what welfare is actually going to cost.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cNot everyone likes the message of tax increases \u2014 that is something we understood going into this campaign \u2014 but most Norwegians understand that welfare also costs money, and, as you probably know, most of our welfare is paid for by taxes,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aDodgy strategy\u000a\u000aIt\u2019s a message that some Norwegians might find hard to take coming from the 57-year-old Støre. Although he leads the traditional party of the Norwegian working class, Støre has a patrician background and is an heir to considerable wealth. He was educated at the Royal Norwegian Naval Academy and the Institut d\u2019études politiques de Paris, followed by a fellowship at Harvard, and served as Stoltenberg\u2019s foreign minister from 2005-2012. While exuding an air of competence and dedication, he can come across as a somewhat aloof, intellectual figure.\u000a\u000aIn Solberg, Norway\u2019s second female prime minister after Gro Harlem Brundtland, Støre faces one of the country\u2019s most popular politicians. Nicknamed \u201cIron Erna,\u201d she has softened in office into someone \u201cyou might even imagine having a drink with,\u201d as one Norwegian reporter put it.\u000a\u000aA recent opinion poll put Solberg ahead of Støre, by 44 percent to 41 percent, when voters were asked who they want as prime minister. However, Norwegians vote for parties and not for the prime minister at the ballot box.\u000a\u000aOther more relevant polls have Støre\u2019s bloc with a narrow lead, but Solberg\u2019s center-right has closed the gap to next to nothing, and some polls even have her bloc ahead.\u000a\u000aSo how has the election-year pledge to raise taxes worked?\u000a\u000a\u201cIt does not seem to have worked very well,\u201d said Aardal, \u201cbecause, first of all, tax is not a good campaign issue for the social democratic [Labor] party. It has been a much better issue for the Conservatives.\u201d\u000a\u000aLabor supporter Anders Tangen, a 50-year-old motivational speaker and radio and TV personality, said it was wrong to see tax hikes as a goal in themselves. \u201cIt is more like a way of getting things done, and what is important for me is that the Norwegian welfare system functions well,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000a\u201cWe have seen in the last year that they [the government] have used so much money from our oil fund, and I think we need more balance on this,\u201d Tangen said. \u201cI think it is honest to say that if we are going to do what we want to do, we have to raise taxes. I think it is an honest thing, and there is some dignity in it.\u201d\u000a\u000aSitting on cash\u000a\u000aIf Labor fails to inspire voters between now and election day, running on a platform to increase taxes will be one of the criticisms that will be leveled at Støre, Aardal said.\u000a\u000aThe main plank in Labor\u2019s election campaign has been that Solberg\u2019s government has done a poor job of managing the economy. Unfortunately for the challenger, the economy has not cooperated with that argument.\u000a\u000aNorth Sea oil and gas producer Norway\u2019s economy was hit hard by the plunge in oil prices in 2014-2016, with unemployment spiking to a 20-year high in 2016. But oil has recovered from its trough of below $30/barrel to current levels of around $50/barrel, joblessness has fallen back to 4.4 percent and GDP grew by a better-than-expected 0.7 percent in the second quarter.\u000a\u000aConsumer confidence has sprung back from an all-time low in December 2015 to a 10-year high 20 months later.\u000a\u000aAnd when the economy sours in Norway, it\u2019s never quite as bad as elsewhere because the country has used its petroleum revenues to build up an almost $1 trillion financial buffer in the world\u2019s largest sovereign wealth fund.\u000a\u000aLargely under pressure from the Progress Party, the government took more money out of the fund in 2016 than went in for the first time since it was established in 1996, prompting cries of mismanagement from the opposition.\u000a\u000aThe government is allowed to spend a small portion of the oil fund annually to plug budget gaps, and it lowered the cap on yearly spending of the fund to 3 percent from 4 percent, with support from the Labor Party and others. But that was not enough to stop Støre\u2019s party from blaming the government for squandering the nation\u2019s wealth to give tax cuts to the wealthy.\u000a\u000aThe first preliminary election results will be published at 9 p.m. local time (7 p.m. GMT), and a full tally could be available by around midnight.
