aVBritish politician and former UKIP leader Nigel Farage speaks at an event held by the right-wing, populist Alternative for Germany political party on September 8, 2017 in Berlin | Sean Gallup/Getty Images Nigel Farage urges German populists to campaign on Brexit Former UKIP leader says he\u2019s \u2018very keen\u2019 to contribute to debate.\u000a\u000aBERLIN \u2014 Nigel Farage urged the right-wing, populist Alternative for Germany (AfD) to make Brexit an issue in the final stretch of the German general election campaign.\u000a\u000aOn a visit to Berlin with just over two weeks to go until polling day, he also called on the AfD to pressure Chancellor Angela Merkel to get the EU to make concessions to the U.K. in its divorce negotiations.\u000a\u000a\u201cNobody talks about Brexit, nobody talks about what the implications of Brexit for Germany would be,\u201d the former leader of the U.K. Independence Party (UKIP) told journalists Friday afternoon before addressing AfD supporters at a campaign event in a Renaissance fortress on the outskirts of Berlin.\u000a\u000a\u201cI\u2019m very keen, if I possibly can, to inject something into this debate,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aHis visit to the German capital followed a personal invitation by AfD deputy chief Beatrix von Storch, a fellow member of the European Parliament, who joined Farage\u2019s Euroskeptic Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy (EFDD) group last year.\u000a\u000aAddressing a predominantly male crowd, surrounded by AfD posters demanding \u201ccourage for the truth,\u201d Farage stressed he had \u201cno formal ties with the AfD as a political party\u201d and was \u201cnot coming here to suggest what people should do.\u201d\u000a\u000aNonetheless, he concluded 30 minutes later, \u201cwith two weeks to go [until the election], I would urge Beatrix and others \u2026 to make Brexit a debate that matters.\u201d\u000a\u000aIn a wide-ranging speech, Farage encouraged the AfD to advocate for facilitating the U.K.\u2019s access to the European Union\u2019s single market after Brexit, while accusing EU leaders and their chief negotiator of \u201cdoing all they can to make sure Brexit doesn\u2019t happen,\u201d by imposing impossible demands on London.\u000a\u000aAt the same time, he accused Merkel, who has repeatedly stressed that there will be \u201cno cherry-picking\u201d for the U.K. in the Brexit talks, of ignoring the interests of German businesses.\u000a\u000a\u201cMerkel needs to know that unless she tells Brussels, \u2018Look please come to common sense,\u2019 then she will be putting the interests of Brussels above the interests of common German people,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000a\u2018Speak the unspeakable\u2019\u000a\u000aMerkel\u2019s conservatives lead comfortably at around 38 percent in recent polls \u2014 about 15 percentage points ahead of the party of her key rival, former European Parliament President Martin Schulz \u2014 and a fourth term for the longtime chancellor seems highly likely.\u000a\u000aThe German parliament, however, is still expected to undergo a major change, with the AfD, founded in 2013 and currently polling at between 8 and 11 percent, widely expected to become the first far-right party to enter the Bundestag.\u000a\u000a\u201cFor the first time in modern history, there is going to be a voice of opposition in the national parliament in Germany,\u201d Farage said cheerfully, \u201cand [other German politicians] are very scared of this happening, indeed.\u201d\u000a\u000aDrawing parallels to the ascent of UKIP over the last 25 years, Farage told the AfD\u2019s von Storch and her party supporters that \u201conce you have the opportunity, once you have the space, once you have the territory to challenge the establishment\u2019s status quo, you have the ability to make the country think.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cOnce you\u2019re able to speak the unspeakable, people will begin to think the unthinkable, and this is how you beat the establishment,\u201d he said.
